INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (3,'ac58c956-6771-4bb3-84a5-ed22dc48e128','Zanzibar Mix','zanzibar-mix','<p>Ancient Omani history, a Portuguese legacy, modern Swahili culture and a melting pot of Islamic beliefs meet in the humid, winding gullies of Zanzibar Islandâ€™s Stonetown. Bikes ring bells constantly and weave around those on foot, coconut water (madafu) sunbathes on sidewalks, and fresh cut mangos with chilies are the refreshing snack of choice.</p><p>Foodies would find the choices here surprising and adventurous. I met Shariffa in a small dark room with exposed coral walls and only two benches pushed roughly to one corner for customers. She massages dal bhajias (lentils) quickly and expertly into neat round balls and tosses them into a vat of oil.</p><p>Her food is cooked on a coal stove. Three women in Islamic dress are enjoying a bowl of the famous mix and nod in encouragement as I ask about the famous food. My tour guide Salim orders the mix and we sit outside on a step in the street and chat about the extraordinary amount of cats wandering about. Apparently the Omanis treasured the dozens of cats they had as a status symbol in the aristocratic homes. They had to leave in a hurry when they came under attack and left their four legged creatures behind. The cats multiplied and roam the town even today.</p><p>Ten minutes later I dive into the dal bhajia that sits in a mango pulp mixture, shaved cassava, boiled potatoes and delicious coconut chutney. The recipe maximizes on the availability and flavor of easily available local food ingredients on the island. Itâ€™s remarkably fresh. Itâ€™s spicy and sweet. For those with steely stomachs, I recommend it. Shariffaâ€™s is one of the most popular places in Stonetown and she does a roaring business. Sheâ€™s not interested in expanding it, she says, she has a roof over her head and can put food on the table. No franchises here.</p>','<p>Ancient Omani history, a Portuguese legacy, modern Swahili culture and a melting pot of Islamic beliefs meet in the humid, winding gullies of Zanzibar Islandâ€™s Stonetown. Bikes ring bells constantly and weave around those on foot, coconut water (madafu) sunbathes on sidewalks, and fresh cut mangos with chilies are the refreshing snack of choice.</p><p>Foodies would find the choices here surprising and adventurous. I met Shariffa in a small dark room with exposed coral walls and only two benches pushed roughly to one corner for customers. She massages dal bhajias (lentils) quickly and expertly into neat round balls and tosses them into a vat of oil.</p><p>Her food is cooked on a coal stove. Three women in Islamic dress are enjoying a bowl of the famous mix and nod in encouragement as I ask about the famous food. My tour guide Salim orders the mix and we sit outside on a step in the street and chat about the extraordinary amount of cats wandering about. Apparently the Omanis treasured the dozens of cats they had as a status symbol in the aristocratic homes. They had to leave in a hurry when they came under attack and left their four legged creatures behind. The cats multiplied and roam the town even today.</p><p>Ten minutes later I dive into the dal bhajia that sits in a mango pulp mixture, shaved cassava, boiled potatoes and delicious coconut chutney. The recipe maximizes on the availability and flavor of easily available local food ingredients on the island. Itâ€™s remarkably fresh. Itâ€™s spicy and sweet. For those with steely stomachs, I recommend it. Shariffaâ€™s is one of the most popular places in Stonetown and she does a roaring business. Sheâ€™s not interested in expanding it, she says, she has a roof over her head and can put food on the table. No franchises here.</p>','/content/images/2015/05/zanzibar_mix-1.jpg',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'My experience with the diverse and delicious food of Zanzibar.',3,'2015-05-09 15:38:55',1,'2015-06-20 00:36:12',1,'2015-05-09 15:38:55',1,2),(4,'ba0ec1e7-37f4-475a-9d22-25c368265d4d','The Mama and I','the-mama-and-i','<p>Well, it\'s time to get this party started once again this semesterâ€¦Iâ€™m sitting in disbelief at the amount of stuff I have due next week. I thought this was my final semester in b-school, whatâ€™s all this work coming at me about? Someone must have been smoking the green stuff when they claimed this would be an easy semester, because it is pretty evident that my professors are intent on making my behind work like an animal this semester.Iâ€™m still going to Brazil and Argentina, thatâ€™s for real (ended up having a ball in South America). I donâ€™t care if I have a midterm the day after spring break.</p><p>So it seems a lot has happened while we all took off and did the do during the holidays (wrote this right after the elections). Now, we have an MBA as the president of the country. Iâ€™m not necessarily jumping up for joy, I mean, this puts the MBA crowd in the spotlight and it doesnâ€™t make it any better that heâ€™s from Harvard. We all know their work ethic, so if Dubya blows the economy or screws up the countryâ€™s fiscal policy, then MBA recruiters are going to start re-evaluating their relationships with business schools. Now, if he was a Stern MBA, with a couple of courses with Messrs. Smith and Yermack, then I would feel a lot more confident (ok, so it gets a little competitive amongst b-schools, that\'s why MBAs are such a sorry bunch). Weâ€™ll watch and see, G.W. Donâ€™t go starting a war with Hawaii (yes it is one of the 50 states, Dubya) or Puerto Rico when stuff hits the fan, you better dig into your â€œConflicts and Negotiationsâ€ textbook and handle your business, boy (wow, it\'s almost like I knew this bobo would start something...damn!!).</p><p>So I had an interesting vacation. Iâ€™m sitting at home, watching TV when I got a phone call from my mother in Nigeria . We talked for a little bit, yâ€™know, I missed her, she missed me, my grandfather (Pimp Daddy Extraordinaire) was married (he\'s about 95 years old...I want to be like him when I grow up. Pimp Daddy!!)â€¦yâ€™know, the good stuff.</p><p>Then she got silent.â€œMama,â€ I inquired, â€œare you alright?â€ Now, in most African cultures, once your parents or elders take a long pause (the pauses have gradually increased as the wedding day gets nearer) when they are speaking to you, your ass is about to get toasted. Dunked on. Plastered. I heard her exhale on the other end. â€œChidi, my son,â€ she started. My heart did a triple axle-trifecta-double-pumped somersault. I popped two Levitra...sorry, two Tylenol extra strength in anticipation of the migraines headed my way via the phone line.</p><p>She continued, â€œI am proud of you. I am really proud of you. You are about to graduate with an MBA and you are the envy of many of your friends back home in Nigeria (actually, no envy whatsoever. The fact is, I didn\'t become a doctor. That signals failure. If you are a young Nigerian in the States and you are not a doctor or pharmacist, you have failed the Igbo Nation. You are required to denounce you Igbohood sixty days after failure). You have done well and God has blessed me with a first son like you.â€ She paused again.</p><p>Oh, boy.</p><p>Okay, now let me explain what she was doing here. This was a common technique used by our folks when serious topics where discussed. Let me use an anecdote to break it own for you. I attended boarding school in Nigeria. It was the best experience in my life; it was also the most harrowing six years any young man could live through on this planet (high school in Nigeria was just incredible. I have the scars to prove it). Oz? That is Disney World compared to boarding school in Nigeria. Anyways, when I was about fifteen, in Class 5 (which is equivalent to the junior year in high school), we had an occurrence of rat attacks. Yes, rat attacks. Fellas would wake up in the morning and discover parts of their toes missing. You would be sleeping in your corner and then get jolted awake by the piercing scream of some poor sonofabitch, whose pinkie toe was now half there, half gone. At first we thought that the spirits of Rumuokwuta were finally exacting justice upon the poor pinkie-less souls, but we had to investigate.</p><p>A nocturnal investigative team was formed to find out what was going on. I ran point on the team. What we saw shocked even myself, who had connections with the spirit world (we still talk, but we had a falling out. always scaring me half to death). At approximately ten to fifteen minutes after two in the morning, as we regaled each other with tales from the crypt, these humongous rats would come out of the woodworks, sneak into the dorm room and position themselves right at the juiciest feet on the lower bunk beds. Then they would nibble a bit on the toe, then blow softly on the toe to intercept and obliterate any pain signals going to the poor guyâ€™s brain. Nibble, blow, nibble, blow (i swear!!). The poor guy wouldnâ€™t feel a thing.</p><p>You see, I was getting the â€œnibble, blowâ€ treatment from The Mama.</p><p>â€œSo, my son. I need to ask you a question.â€ I popped two more Tylenols.</p><p>â€œWhen are you going to get married?â€</p><p>Whoa. (yeah...like whoa!)</p><p>The Mama started tearing into me. â€œAll your friends here in Nigeria have gotten married (every single one of them). I went to Okeyâ€™s wedding last week. In fact, Kelechi is about to have her second baby.â€</p><p>I was speechless. Kelechi? Her second baby? Damn. She was fine, too. Now thatâ€™s someone I could have married (thank God I didn\'t. I heard she went psycho on her husband, and got a job).</p><p>â€œWellâ€¦uhâ€¦Mamaâ€¦yâ€™seeâ€¦â€ I was stuttering like a Stern MBA at a Bain interview.</p><p>â€œDonâ€™t you â€˜wellâ€¦uhâ€™ me. Look, you are old enough to father as many children as the head cockerel on our compound (true, true). Tell me, Chidi, what are you waiting for, eh?â€ (uh, graduation? A job? Some money? How about a woman?) The Mama was getting heated and I was not helping by cowering on the other end of the line. I had to mount a strong defense.</p><p>â€œBut, Mama,â€ I countered, â€œI am going to school. I have no money, I donâ€™t even have a job, what woman would want a broke man like me. I canâ€™t even buy water.â€ Now, that was a good counter-attack.</p><p>â€œShaaarrraaappp, you idiotâ€, The Mama bellowed into the phone. â€œWhat do you mean you are broke, eh? Didnâ€™t you tell me some of your classmates are being offered salaries of two hundred thousand dollars a year? (ok...so maybe I exagerrated a little bit there). I have told everyone you will be making at least three hundred thousand since you are smarter than all of them, right? (now this is bordering on delusional). Didnâ€™t you tell me you already had an offer? â€</p><p>Typical Naija. Four rapid fire sentences, and they all ended with question marks.</p><p>Damn. I fed her all that stuff so she could feel like this MBA thing was a good idea. Now she was using it against me. And there was no way I was going to start explaining that the economy was â€œrecedingâ€ some of those freaking gazillion, pravillion dollar offers. My mother is brilliant. I never could beat her in an argument, and I usually donâ€™t lose my arguments (well, since The Ngozi showed up, I have been losing consistently every day).</p><p>She shoved aside the money issue. â€œI know you will make money, that is not a concern for me. I think it is time for you to get married and have children. Some of my friends have seen your pictures from America and they have come to visit me with their daughters.â€ She stopped to hear my reaction. I inhaled deeply. I knew this was bound to happen soon, so I pretty much acquiesced and asked her what she wanted me to do. I heard the rustling of paper on her end. The Mama always had her stuff together.</p><p>â€œWell, I have five girls that I really like. Their families are very well respected and these girls were raised very properly.â€ I could hear her smiling (i admit, I was smiling too).</p><p>â€œThese girls are beautiful too. Do you remember Nkiru?â€ Yes, I remembered Nkiru. She dumped me like used toilet paper when I was sixteen. Now she wanted to marry me. Iâ€™m sure the picture of me beside my ex-bossâ€™s Escalade XLT had nothing do with her sudden affection for me.</p><p>As I listened to her, I couldnâ€™t help but note how absurd it all sounded. Who told her I wanted someone who was raised properly? Why couldnâ€™t I get one of those booty-shaking girls in all those hip-hop videos (you know, I did end up with a booty shaking girl...heh-heh. Sorry, the Ngozi)?</p><p>The Mama then finished with one of her patented concluding statements. â€œWhy donâ€™t you come home in May and visit me? And you can also meet these girls, you might like one of them. I also have some presents that I have bought for youâ€¦actually, my friends bought them for you. Chidi, you know I love you, right?â€œ</p><p>Nibble, blow, nibble, blow.</p>','<p>Well, it\'s time to get this party started once again this semesterâ€¦Iâ€™m sitting in disbelief at the amount of stuff I have due next week. I thought this was my final semester in b-school, whatâ€™s all this work coming at me about? Someone must have been smoking the green stuff when they claimed this would be an easy semester, because it is pretty evident that my professors are intent on making my behind work like an animal this semester.Iâ€™m still going to Brazil and Argentina, thatâ€™s for real (ended up having a ball in South America). I donâ€™t care if I have a midterm the day after spring break.</p><p>So it seems a lot has happened while we all took off and did the do during the holidays (wrote this right after the elections). Now, we have an MBA as the president of the country. Iâ€™m not necessarily jumping up for joy, I mean, this puts the MBA crowd in the spotlight and it doesnâ€™t make it any better that heâ€™s from Harvard. We all know their work ethic, so if Dubya b