lowâ€ treatment from The Mama.</p><p>â€œSo, my son. I need to ask you a question.â€ I popped two more Tylenols.</p><p>â€œWhen are you going to get married?â€</p><p>Whoa. (yeah...like whoa!)</p><p>The Mama started tearing into me. â€œAll your friends here in Nigeria have gotten married (every single one of them). I went to Okeyâ€™s wedding last week. In fact, Kelechi is about to have her second baby.â€</p><p>I was speechless. Kelechi? Her second baby? Damn. She was fine, too. Now thatâ€™s someone I could have married (thank God I didn\'t. I heard she went psycho on her husband, and got a job).</p><p>â€œWellâ€¦uhâ€¦Mamaâ€¦yâ€™seeâ€¦â€ I was stuttering like a Stern MBA at a Bain interview.</p><p>â€œDonâ€™t you â€˜wellâ€¦uhâ€™ me. Look, you are old enough to father as many children as the head cockerel on our compound (true, true). Tell me, Chidi, what are you waiting for, eh?â€ (uh, graduation? A job? Some money? How about a woman?) The Mama was getting heated and I was not helping by cowering on the other end of the line. I had to mount a strong defense.</p><p>â€œBut, Mama,â€ I countered, â€œI am going to school. I have no money, I donâ€™t even have a job, what woman would want a broke man like me. I canâ€™t even buy water.â€ Now, that was a good counter-attack.</p><p>â€œShaaarrraaappp, you idiotâ€, The Mama bellowed into the phone. â€œWhat do you mean you are broke, eh? Didnâ€™t you tell me some of your classmates are being offered salaries of two hundred thousand dollars a year? (ok...so maybe I exagerrated a little bit there). I have told everyone you will be making at least three hundred thousand since you are smarter than all of them, right? (now this is bordering on delusional). Didnâ€™t you tell me you already had an offer? â€</p><p>Typical Naija. Four rapid fire sentences, and they all ended with question marks.</p><p>Damn. I fed her all that stuff so she could feel like this MBA thing was a good idea. Now she was using it against me. And there was no way I was going to start explaining that the economy was â€œrecedingâ€ some of those freaking gazillion, pravillion dollar offers. My mother is brilliant. I never could beat her in an argument, and I usually donâ€™t lose my arguments (well, since The Ngozi showed up, I have been losing consistently every day).</p><p>She shoved aside the money issue. â€œI know you will make money, that is not a concern for me. I think it is time for you to get married and have children. Some of my friends have seen your pictures from America and they have come to visit me with their daughters.â€ She stopped to hear my reaction. I inhaled deeply. I knew this was bound to happen soon, so I pretty much acquiesced and asked her what she wanted me to do. I heard the rustling of paper on her end. The Mama always had her stuff together.</p><p>â€œWell, I have five girls that I really like. Their families are very well respected and these girls were raised very properly.â€ I could hear her smiling (i admit, I was smiling too).</p><p>â€œThese girls are beautiful too. Do you remember Nkiru?â€ Yes, I remembered Nkiru. She dumped me like used toilet paper when I was sixteen. Now she wanted to marry me. Iâ€™m sure the picture of me beside my ex-bossâ€™s Escalade XLT had nothing do with her sudden affection for me.</p><p>As I listened to her, I couldnâ€™t help but note how absurd it all sounded. Who told her I wanted someone who was raised properly? Why couldnâ€™t I get one of those booty-shaking girls in all those hip-hop videos (you know, I did end up with a booty shaking girl...heh-heh. Sorry, the Ngozi)?</p><p>The Mama then finished with one of her patented concluding statements. â€œWhy donâ€™t you come home in May and visit me? And you can also meet these girls, you might like one of them. I also have some presents that I have bought for youâ€¦actually, my friends bought them for you. Chidi, you know I love you, right?â€œ</p><p>Nibble, blow, nibble, blow.</p>','/content/images/2015/05/BONIFACE_MWANGI017.jpg',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Here\'s a little something I wrote for my column in b-school during the spring of 2001. Is it fiction or is it fact? I can\'t remember. In fact, I deny anything that should be denied. But, I hope you enjoy. I added a couple of comments in italics.',8,'2015-05-09 17:13:30',1,'2015-06-05 03:41:15',2,'2015-05-09 17:13:30',1,0),(5,'01383bb6-149c-497b-8b63-d8ec4e7652c8','The Lagos Tech Scene','the-lagos-tech-scene','<p>mashable asks \"is lagos home to an african tech movement?\"</p><p>yes. it is.</p><p>let me break it down for you.</p><p>it\'s all about mobile and nigeria is a mobile haven, with most individuals rolling with at least two mobile phones from one or more of the incumbent carriers. estimates are that there were over 110m active mobile subscriptions in nigeria, by fall of 2012, compared to under 474k fixed lines. mobile penetration is hovering around 65% for a population of over 160 million people, according to world bank estimates.</p><p>the startup scene is hot. there is konga, that has aspirations to be the amazon of africa. the online megastore was founded by sim shagaya, former head of google africa.</p><p>not to be outdone, jumia, another online retailer and subsidiary of german incubator rocket internet, erected a 12,000 square foot warehouse in lagos in 2012.</p><p>wakanow is former nba and maryland center obinna ekezie\'s online travel website that is doing brisk business for travellers in sub-saharan africa.</p><p>if you haven\'t watched a nollywood (nigeria\'s booming movie industry) movie, then irokotv is your digital destination to catch up on your flicks. part netflix, part imdb, irokotv\'s jason njoku has cornered the market for nollywood svod. replace three letters in irokotv and you have ibakatv, which is also a nollywood online viewing destination.</p><p>of course, money transfer startups are sprouting up in this cash based economy. paga has captured the lead for mobile payments and transfers in nigeria.</p><p>looking for a gig in nigeria - jobberman has your back.</p><p>need to buy a ride? check out cheki nigeria.</p><p>the big names have all landed in lagos. microsoft is active in the dev community. google nigeria provides its potent suite of online platforms and apps to businesses and celebrities, including google trader. there is a brand new apple istore, opened in dec \'12. blackberry and nokia compete for mobile device domination in the nigerian market.</p><p>co creation hub nigeria or, cchub as it is more well known as, is a primary focal point, pre-incubation and gathering spot for the tech community in lagos.</p><p>even the tech blogging scene in naija is blossoming nicely with outfits such as techloy, otekbits, and tech360.</p><p>the nigerian tech scene is happening. and lagos is at the heart of it all.</p><p>so, yes, lagos is home to a burgeoning african tech scene. get on board.</p>','<p>mashable asks \"is lagos home to an african tech movement?\"</p><p>yes. it is.</p><p>let me break it down for you.</p><p>it\'s all about mobile and nigeria is a mobile haven, with most individuals rolling with at least two mobile phones from one or more of the incumbent carriers. estimates are that there were over 110m active mobile subscriptions in nigeria, by fall of 2012, compared to under 474k fixed lines. mobile penetration is hovering around 65% for a population of over 160 million people, according to world bank estimates.</p><p>the startup scene is hot. there is konga, that has aspirations to be the amazon of africa. the online megastore was founded by sim shagaya, former head of google africa.</p><p>not to be outdone, jumia, another online retailer and subsidiary of german incubator rocket internet, erected a 12,000 square foot warehouse in lagos in 2012.</p><p>wakanow is former nba and maryland center obinna ekezie\'s online travel website that is doing brisk business for travellers in sub-saharan africa.</p><p>if you haven\'t watched a nollywood (nigeria\'s booming movie industry) movie, then irokotv is your digital destination to catch up on your flicks. part netflix, part imdb, irokotv\'s jason njoku has cornered the market for nollywood svod. replace three letters in irokotv and you have ibakatv, which is also a nollywood online viewing destination.</p><p>of course, money transfer startups are sprouting up in this cash based economy. paga has captured the lead for mobile payments and transfers in nigeria.</p><p>looking for a gig in nigeria - jobberman has your back.</p><p>need to buy a ride? check out cheki nigeria.</p><p>the big names have all landed in lagos. microsoft is active in the dev community. google nigeria provides its potent suite of online platforms and apps to businesses and celebrities, including google trader. there is a brand new apple istore, opened in dec \'12. blackberry and nokia compete for mobile device domination in the nigerian market.</p><p>co creation hub nigeria or, cchub as it is more well known as, is a primary focal point, pre-incubation and gathering spot for the tech community in lagos.</p><p>even the tech blogging scene in naija is blossoming nicely with outfits such as techloy, otekbits, and tech360.</p><p>the nigerian tech scene is happening. and lagos is at the heart of it all.</p><p>so, yes, lagos is home to a burgeoning african tech scene. get on board.</p>','/content/images/2015/05/Lagos.jpg',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'A lot is made about Silicon Valley, Silicon Alley and other bastions of technology and innovation. The tech scenes in Africa don\'t get as much attention, so I figured that I highlight the burgeoning startup and technology activity that is happening in Nigeria\'s big city, Lagos.',8,'2015-05-09 17:29:04',1,'2015-05-09 17:35:15',1,'2015-05-09 17:31:56',1,0),(6,'59e364eb-638b-4111-9a5b-83aa0b9b84f5','Why Do We Still Need the Constitution?','why-do-we-still-need-the-constitution','<p>The Constitution is the defining document of our countryâ€™s government. Since its inception in 1787, the Constitution has molded the fabric of our nationâ€™s governing policies. But in the face of growing partisanship and an increased inability to reach a consensus on basic ideals, critics question if the Constitution is still the best way to govern the United States.</p><p>Our Government under the Constitution</p><p>The Constitution outlines the principles with which to govern our country.</p><p>The first ten amendments, known as the Bill of Rights, gives Americans various rights including protection against self-incrimination and the right to bear arms. Even the process of checks and balances, presidential term limitations, and womenâ€™s voting rights are covered in this historic document.</p><p>Why the Constitution should remain</p><p>Proponents of the governance by the Constitution say the country runs efficiently under the Constitution. Why change what works? In addition to providing rights and privileges to Americans, Constitutional amendments have adapted to issues facing our modern society. There have been 27 amendments to the Constitution since its inception; which have addressed specific issues facing the country at the time. For example the 13th Amendment was included to abolish slavery in the 1860s and the 19th gave women the right to vote. These amendments are indications that the Constitution can be kept current and relevant to changing times and paradigms.</p><p>The Constitution has also made it possible to keep all branches of the government in check. Without it, the executive branch or event the legislative branch of the government would have unlimited powers and would undermine the very definition of democracy. In essence, proponents say the Constitution safeguards American democracy.</p><p>Has the Constitution kept up with the times?</p><p>However, critics against the Constitution have been equally vocal. They see it as an outdated document and question the effectiveness of something that was written hundreds of years ago. In a New York Times Op-Ed article, Georgetown professor Mike Seidman even questions why we would loyally follow a document written by men that believed women had no place in government and that it was appropriate to own other humans. There have also many arguments against the Constitutionâ€™s views on gun ownership. When the Second Amendment was added to the Constitution in 1791, the United States was a new country and just barely out of the war with England. The initial purpose of the amendment was to offer Americans the opportunity to protect their homes and states in the chance of another war. Our founding fathers could not foresee the advances in technology in weaponry and the amount of destruction that could be caused by guns. Critics of the Constitution claim this is yet another sign that the document is outdated and out of touch.</p><p>There have also many debates about completely doing away with the Constitution. But would it be possible or even advantageous to do this? Opponents argue that Americans should follow amendments like freedom of speech and religion out of respect. However, updating or doing away with controversial amendments like the 2nd Amendment (The right to bear arms) would be much harder due to political polarization.</p><p>In fact, political polarization is so strong in this country that making any amendments to the Constitution is incredibly difficult. There have been over 11,000 attempts to amend the Constitution but only 27 have been successful. In this case, political polarization may be too difficult to overcome.</p><p>Do you think the Constitution is still relevant? Should there be a major overhaul? Do you think the parties could come together to make a significant change?</p>','<p>The Constitution is the defining document of our countryâ€™s government. Since its inception in 1787, the Constitution has molded the fabric of our nationâ€™s governing policies. But in the face of growing partisanship and an increased inability to reach a consensus on basic ideals, critics question if the Constitution is still the best way to govern the United States.</p><p>Our Government under the Constitution</p><p>The Constitution outlines the principles with which to govern our country.</p><p>The first ten amendments, known as the Bill of Rights, gives Americans various rights including protection against self-incrimination and the right to bear arms. Even the process of checks and balances, presidential term limitations, and womenâ€™s voting rights are covered in this historic document.</p><p>Why the Constitution should remain</p><p>Proponents of the governance by the Constitution say the country runs efficiently under the Constitution. Why change what works? In addition to providing rights and privileges to Americans, Constitutional amendments have adapted to issues facing our modern society. There have been 27 amendments to the Constitution since its inception; which have addressed specific issues facing the country at the time. For example the 13th Amendment was included to abolish slavery in the 1860s and the 19th gave women the right to vote. These amendments are indications that the Constitution can be kept current and relevant to changing times and paradigms.</p><p>The Constitution has also made it possible to keep all branches of the government in check. Without it, the executive branch or event the legislative branch of the government would have unlimited powers and would undermine the very definition of democracy. In essence, proponents say the Constitution safeguards American democracy.</p><p>Has the Constitution kept up with the times?</p><p>However, critics against the Constitution have been equally vocal. They see it as an outdated document and question the effectiveness of something that was written hundreds of years ago. In a New York Times Op-Ed article, Georgetown professor Mike Seidman even questions why we would loyally follow a document written by men that believed women had no place in government and that it was appropriate to own other humans. There have also many arguments against the Constitutionâ€™s views on gun ownership. When the Second Amendment was added to the Constitution in 1791, the United States was a new country and just barely out of the war with England. The initial purpose of the amendment was to offer Americans the opportunity to protect their homes and states in the chance of another war. Our founding fathers could not foresee the advances in technology in weaponry and the amount of destruction that could be caused by guns. Critics of the Constitution claim this is yet another sign that the document is outdated and out of touch.</p><p>There have also many debates about completely doing away with the Constitution. But would it be possible or even advantageous to do this? Opponents argue that Americans should follow amendments like freedom of speech and religion out of respect. However, updating or doing away with controversial amendments like the 2nd Amendment (The right to bear arms) would be much harder due to political polarization.</p><p>In fact, political polarization is so strong in this country that making any amendments to the Constitution is incredibly difficult. There have been over 11,000 attempts to amend the Constitution but only 27 have been successful. In this case, political polarization may be too difficult to overcome.</p><p>Do you think the Constitution is still relevant? Should there be a major overhaul? Do you think the parties could come together to make a significant change?</p>','/content/images/2015/05/oldguys.jpg',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'The U.S Constitution is over 300 years old and a lot has changed in this country since then. I take a look at why the Constitution might be irrelevant in our modern times while also taking a look at it\'s value.',5,'2015-05-09 17:38:37',1,'2015-06-20 00:36:52',1,'2015-05-09 17:40:16',1,1),(7,'8e435166-e71f-4d71-9b2b-3416d23e6ff5','The Survival Kit','the-survival-kit','<p><font color=\"#4d4d4d\" face=\"Helvetica Neue, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px;\">We were all laughing at the young lady behind us. She was clutching for, pretty much anything. Her seat, the seat in front of her, the seat behind her including the people in those seats. She was probably saying her final prayers. â€œIf I survive this I will become a nun, please Lordâ€. The other lady next to me kept explaining with a heavy Danish accent that they were warned about our (in)famous Matatus. Unfortunately for them the driver was having a \'party of the lanes\' much to her disgust. â€œThis is very different from Odenseâ€, she insisted.</span></font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">For those of us who are used to it, we will tell you that we have experienced a little bit of everything from our daily commutes. Near death experiences to ones that were more humorous than deadly, a run in with traffic police to meeting interesting people. I said meeting but I really meant staring. From fancy ones that have all kinds of graffiti, lights and loud music to the old has beens that need the tout to occasionally carry the door all by his lonesome. You cant escape using them. Anywhere you want to go, there is a matatu that will most likely get you there. They are the most used means of transport in Kenya.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">For my all interaction with matatus, I have come to grow accustomed to all it\'s horseplay. To develop a level of tolerance I came up with a \'daily survival kit\' for what to do when in a matatu. In all my commutes this kit has never failed me. Someone cc WikiHow.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\"><b>Choose The Best Seat</b></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">If you can, because believe me you don\'t want to end up seated next to the lady that takes up her seat plus half of yours, has like five kids who wont stop crying and is carrying more luggages than she has hands. You will come out of the matatu with a certificate in fatherhood and luggage handling. So what is the best seat in the house you ask? The one behind the conductor. Its a single seat which means I don\'t have to deal with anyone more than myself. When you want to alight, you don\'t bother anyone and no one else bothers you when they are alighting. Perfect. I don\'t always get this seat but when I do, its one less thing to worry about.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\"><span style=\"font-weight: 700;\">Earphones</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">Listen, I don\'t advocate for asocial behavior, but if you\'ve ever had a heated political debate with someone who had eggs and an onion inspired meal for breakfast at 7am on A MONDAY MORNING you will understand where I am coming from. You cant take that conversation back. Neither can you take his breathe away (Pun). Worse still you are sat where the window just wont budge open. Jesus didn\'t wash away my sins for this. Never forget your earphones.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\"><span style=\"font-weight: 700;\">A Sense of Humor.</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">Crazy things happen. They always do. They should set up a Matatus Anonymous. I imagine the stories that will come out would easily beat The Audacity of Hope to the Pulitzer. You need to have a sense of humor. Just yesterday, as I was headed home from the city center and everyone was doing their thing, we started hearing strange noises from the back of the matatu. It was so strange and loud that it caused quite a commotion. After a brief inquiry, a lot of debate and the driver actually having to pull over to the side of the road, we finally discovered that there was a goat at the back below the seats. It\'s owner quietly asleep as we scratched our heads. We had a good laugh!</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">I hope this helps some sorry soul out there!</p>','<p><font color=\"#4d4d4d\" face=\"Helvetica Neue, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px; line-height: 18px;\">We were all laughing at the young lady behind us. She was clutching for, pretty much anything. Her seat, the seat in front of her, the seat behind her including the people in those seats. She was probably saying her final prayers. â€œIf I survive this I will become a nun, please Lordâ€. The other lady next to me kept explaining with a heavy Danish accent that they were warned about our (in)famous Matatus. Unfortunately for them the driver was having a \'party of the lanes\' much to her disgust. â€œThis is very different from Odenseâ€, she insisted.</span></font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">For those of us who are used to it, we will tell you that we have experienced a little bit of everything from our daily commutes. Near death experiences to ones that were more humorous than deadly, a run in with traffic police to meeting interesting people. I said meeting but I really meant staring. From fancy ones that have all kinds of graffiti, lights and loud music to the old has beens that need the tout to occasionally carry the door all by his lonesome. You cant escape using them. Anywhere you want to go, there is a matatu that will most likely get you there. They are the most used means of transport in Kenya.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">For my all interaction with matatus, I have come to grow accustomed to all it\'s horseplay. To develop a level of tolerance I came up with a \'daily survival kit\' for what to do when in a matatu. In all my commutes this kit has never failed me. Someone cc WikiHow.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\"><b>Choose The Best Seat</b></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">If you can, because believe me you don\'t want to end up seated next to the lady that takes up her seat plus half of yours, has like five kids who wont stop crying and is carrying more luggages than she has hands. You will come out of the matatu with a certificate in fatherhood and luggage handling. So what is the best seat in the house you ask? The one behind the conductor. Its a single seat which means I don\'t have to deal with anyone more than myself. When you want to alight, you don\'t bother anyone and no one else bothers you when they are alighting. Perfect. I don\'t always get this seat but when I do, its one less thing to worry about.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\"><span style=\"font-weight: 700;\">Earphones</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">Listen, I don\'t advocate for asocial behavior, but if you\'ve ever had a heated political debate with someone who had eggs and an onion inspired meal for breakfast at 7am on A MONDAY MORNING you will understand where I am coming from. You cant take that conversation back. Neither can you take his breathe away (Pun). Worse still you are sat where the window just wont budge open. Jesus didn\'t wash away my sins for this. Never forget your earphones.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\"><span style=\"font-weight: 700;\">A Sense of Humor.</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">Crazy things happen. They always do. They should set up a Matatus Anonymous. I imagine the stories that will come out would easily beat The Audacity of Hope to the Pulitzer. You need to have a sense of humor. Just yesterday, as I was headed home from the city center and everyone was doing their thing, we started hearing strange noises from the back of the matatu. It was so strange and loud that it caused quite a commotion. After a brief inquiry, a lot of debate and the driver actually having to pull over to the side of the road, we finally discovered that there was a goat at the back below the seats. It\'s owner quietly asleep as we scratched our heads. We had a good laugh!</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 8px; color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">I hope this helps some sorry soul out there!</p>','/content/images/2015/05/The_ocean_stirsthe_heart-_inspiresthe.png',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'For my all interaction with matatus, I have come to grow accustomed to all it\'s horseplay. To develop a level of tolerance I came up with a \'daily survival kit\' for what to do when in a matatu. In all my commutes this kit has never failed me. Someone cc WikiHow.',2,'2015-05-09 17:53:19',1,'2015-06-17 05:22:37',1,'2015-05-09 17:53:50',1,3),(8,'2d478c23-8605-4054-9dcc-a966020baadc','Welcome to aKoma','welcome-to-akoma','<p>I believe in passion. I believe in purpose. I believe in following a dream fearlessly.</p><p>So Iâ€™ve created aKoma: stories made @ africa</p><p>It will start as a writing platform. Next we will do video and TV.</p><p>aKoma needs your voice. Your talent. No filter.</p><p>For many years Iâ€™ve wanted to create a media company that covers the diversity of Africa the way I believe it should be covered. aKoma is my first step.</p><p>Iâ€™m sick of the disaster, war, flies on faces, disease, refugee camps, and terror images of Africa. Iâ€™m sick of associating animals and beaches only with Africa.</p><p>You and I know there is more. So much more. We are one billion people, each of us with lifestyles and aspirations, those in other parts of Africa or the rest of the world know little or nothing about. Well, now they will.</p><p>aKoma means â€œheart.â€ Thatâ€™s the only ingredient I want writers to have on this platform. Put your heart into your storytellerâ€™s voice.</p><p>It can be personal, it can be a crazy idea, it can be as mundane or as moving a topic you want, as short or as long as you like. You can share pictures that grab you, or an image you sketch that captures something meaningful. You can share knowledge and pass on tips, and news you can use.</p><p>I want us to show that we are the land of innovation where the next big idea that will change the world, we have a vibrant lifestyle, an intellecual middle class, entrepreneurial spirit, a creative industry with talent that is mind blowing, our women are trail blazing and leading, we are connected. We have class.</p><p>We have problems too. Cool. We can talk about those openly. We are respectful of differences. We are sophisticated.</p><p>I would like to train, hire or inspire the best Africa focused storytellers who get the most hits and shares to be part of our team.</p><p>My team and I will work hard to bring you the audience you want and to showcase aKoma writers and thinkers. That is our responsibility, and we are going gangster.</p><p>I will share everything iâ€™ve learned after fourteen years at CNN with you. You wonâ€™t need to spend money to buy the book ! I will transfer all my knowledge, and that of my friends and colleagues, to you on aKoma.</p><p>Many of you know I am from Kenya. My family has lived here for more than one hundred years. My great grandfather stood on the same platform as Jomo Kenyatta for independence, Kenya made my career, Kenyans and all Africans around the world have supported me all my life and inspired me to break glass ceilings.</p><p>Let\'s #inspireafrica. Iâ€™m so very proud and excited to introduce aKoma : stories made @ africa.</p><p>Karibuni. Welcome.</p>','<p>I believe in passion. I believe in purpose. I believe in following a dream fearlessly.</p><p>So Iâ€™ve created aKoma: stories made @ africa</p><p>It will start as a writing platform. Next we will do video and TV.</p><p>aKoma needs your voice. Your talent. No filter.</p><p>For many years Iâ€™ve wanted to create a media company that covers the diversity of Africa the way I believe it should be covered. aKoma is my first step.</p><p>Iâ€™m sick of the disaster, war, flies on faces, disease, refugee camps, and terror images of Africa. Iâ€™m sick of associating animals and beaches only with Africa.</p><p>You and I know there is more. So much more. We are one billion people, each of us with lifestyles and aspirations, those in other parts of Africa or the rest of the world know little or nothing about. Well, now they will.</p><p>aKoma means â€œheart.â€ Thatâ€™s the only ingredient I want writers to have on this platform. Put your heart into your storytellerâ€™s voice.</p><p>It can be personal, it can be a crazy idea, it can be as mundane or as moving a topic you want, as short or as long as you like. You can share pictures that grab you, or an image you sketch that captures something meaningful. You can share knowledge and pass on tips, and news you can use.</p><p>I want us to show that we are the land of innovation where the next big idea that will change the world, we have a vibrant lifestyle, an intellecual middle class, entrepreneurial spirit, a creative industry with talent that is mind blowing, our women are trail blazing and leading, we are connected. We have class.</p><p>We have problems too. Cool. We can talk about those openly. We are respectful of differences. We are sophisticated.</p><p>I would like to train, hire or inspire the best Africa focused storytellers who get the most hits and shares to be part of our team.</p><p>My team and I will work hard to bring you the audience you want and to showcase aKoma writers and thinkers. That is our responsibility, and we are going gangster.</p><p>I will share everything iâ€™ve learned after fourteen years at CNN with you. You wonâ€™t need to spend money to buy the book ! I will transfer all my knowledge, and that of my friends and colleagues, to you on aKoma.</p><p>Many of you know I am from Kenya. My family has lived here for more than one hundred years. My great grandfather stood on the same platform as Jomo Kenyatta for independence, Kenya made my career, Kenyans and all Africans around the world have supported me all my life and inspired me to break glass ceilings.</p><p>Let\'s #inspireafrica. Iâ€™m so very proud and excited to introduce aKoma : stories made @ africa.</p><p>Karibuni. Welcome.</p>','/content/images/2015/05/BONIFACE_MWANGI44.JPG',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<span style=\"color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">For many years Iâ€™ve wanted to create a media company that covers the diversity of Africa the way I believe it should be covered. aKoma is my first step.</span>',3,'2015-05-09 17:58:25',1,'2015-06-16 01:23:30',1,'2015-05-09 17:59:02',1,2),(9,'64d8b301-0b08-4f77-94f6-78943d67c0aa','Black Moor Survivors','black-moor-survivors','<p>The crunch of shattered glass beneath my feet, the bullet holes in windows and the acrid smell of disaster enveloped me the moment I entered my favorite mall in Nairobi. It was surreal. Days ago a massacre happened here as friends and family lived out a typical mundane errand and chatter filled Saturday morning.</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 18px; line-height: 34px;\">I felt hollow, paralyzed as the magnitude of the inane bloodshed and violence that occurred lay on a fractured canvas before me. I was dazed. A lump in my throat fought back insistent tears as I recalled numerous coffees at Art CafÃ©, endless ice-cream purchases at Nakumatt, banking with dad upstairs or sharing a strawberry frozen yogurt downstairs.</span></p><p>That store was shot up, I could only imagine the terrified frenzy there, My CNN producer, Victoria Eastwood and I secretly started to film the scenes around us on our i-phones inside Westgate Mall. No media organization had been allowed to enter ground zero that lay between the Parklands and Westlands areas of the city. Chairs lay on the ground and a half finished coffee, signs that ended life in mid sentence.</p><p>We had posed as family members of one shop owner who was there to clear what was left of his store. One hour ago we snuck in with someone who recognized me at Nakumatt Ukay shopping center, and was going to check on his car, one of the few still left pristine and white on the parking deck roof.</p><p>For a long time, I stared at the most shocking space. The rooftop corner where children where learning how to cook before they were ruthlessly gunned down. Burned out remnants remained and I turned my eyes away, to look at the gaping hole on the imploded deck.</p><p>My father and I had walked through this space countless times looking at children play, shopping at the open-air market or validating our tickets and talking. I was as comfortable as Westgate as I am in my own home. It felt personal and it was hollow and horrifying.</p><p>Affluent Nairobi consists of a small circle and we all knew someone who was at the mall, missing from the mall, affected by the mall, hurt or dead.</p><p>In the horror and furor, Nairobi had risen to the occasion, just like its citizens did during the US embassy bombing, when I was there. Every community, every race, medical facilities, religious and political leaders pulled together. The least I could do was pull myself together and do the most professional, objective job I could, and apply only journalism, not emotion, to what I was articulating live on the air.</p><p>For days there were rumors about victims, about terrorists who had escaped, confusion over who had the upper hand terrorists or the security forces, was the mall booby trapped with explosives, was the army looting, where there hostages.</p><p>Iâ€™m not a war reporter. I never aspired towards it. Yet I found myself standing with a flack jacket, helmet and with gunshots ringing out, close to our live position, a Jain religious and cultural center called Oshwall, where grandmas and grandpas often come to walk around the track.</p><p>The advantage of being a local Kenyan was that I knew most people, the public knew me, and most importantly trusted me. This meant I was getting significantly more information than any other journalist, either local or international and I had to be very careful with it.</p><p>I was in communication with senior officials at State House, with the Kenyan intelligence agency, Rwandese intelligence, two British Intelligence contacts and a CIA source. The information I was getting was conflicting, terrifying, and fascinating all at the same time. Everyone at this moment is trying to figure out what is going on. What is real? What is reportable? Much information is unconfirmed or unauthorized for use. I didnâ€™t want to terrify Nairobi, already on edge and in shock, and I didnâ€™t want to report information that was either too sensitive or could be construed as rumor.</p><p>I almost hadnâ€™t made it to Nairobi for this assignment. I had arrived at Oxford University on Saturday morning that September for the first residence of a Masters Degree in Creative Writing and was on vacation, determined nothing would take me away from the mandatory few days.</p><p>Walking back from Costa coffee, the wires started to cross.</p><p>â€˜Gunshots heard at Nairobiâ€™s Westgate Mall.â€™</p><p>â€˜Eyewitnesses report casualties.â€™</p><p>â€˜Terrorists take hostages at Nairobiâ€™s Westgate mall.â€™</p><p>My mouth went dry. My mum and dad often go to Westgate mall on a Saturday morning. I couldnâ€™t get through for a while, and my shirt started to drench with panicked sweat. Oxford phone networks are mind-blowingly lousy and I ran back and forth on the street trying to get a signal, my hands shaking.</p><p>â€œWe are OKâ€ came a text from my father. I exhaled, and started to frantically type a guidance note to CNN editorial about Westgate Mall and what information I was starting to receive. The international desk brought me in for beepers, phone interviews, the rest of the afternoon.. Deborah Rayner, a senior CNN executive, called me and ordered me to cancel Oxford and get on the first plane to Nairobi.</p><p>I hadnâ€™t seen the pictures of the siege for hours and was operating in a video vacuum and didnâ€™t fully comprehend that magnitude of the situation until I arrived home. Before I packed up left amid tears, my father called. He had been on his way to Westgate that morning for an errand and decided that it would be too busy, so fortunately diverted his trip.</p><p>â€œListen, Julie was in Westgate and made it out,â€ he said.</p><p>â€œWhat?â€ I responded, confused as to why he was telling me about my aunt, his older sister, who lives in London. He explained quickly that she and her husband Nizar were on holiday, and in the mall. They hid out, and hours later, made it out while terrorists were inside firing at close range.</p><p>â€œSheâ€™s fine but a bit shaken up,â€ he said.</p><p>â€œSend me her number pleaseâ€, I asked realizing CNN would be able to use an articulate eyewitness account on the air. My aunt was tough and a survivor, she always has been.</p><p>I received many more eyewitness accounts while covering this story, in particular relating to the White Widow, British terrorist Samantha Leiwthwaite, believed to have been the mastermind behind this attack. There exists a photograph circulated among intelligence agencies that believe show her walking out of the mall, in plain sight, along with everyone else fleeing. No one has confirmed this on the record.</p><p>Victoria was an excellent producer who had both a strong editorial mind as well as a logistical and organizational calm under fire, which was stabilizing to any talent. We analyzed all intelligence coming to CNN and decided what was news worthy, what could be backed up, and what could not.</p><p>Victoria quickly came to believe the strength of my sources on the ground. I would receive a text.</p><p>â€œAn explosion is about to happenâ€. Seconds later, it did.</p><p>â€œWear your helmet and flack jacket. Terrorists believed on the loose in your area.â€ Gunfire erupted almost immediately.</p><p>In moments, I felt I was in a really bad action movie. Our family friend Collette, a spa manager and owner on Peponi Road close to the mall, gave the whole CNN team access to bathrooms, shelter from rain, and the use of her kitchen for our planning and analysis â€˜war roomâ€™.</p><p>By now the team was much bigger, Nima el-Bagir and Arwa Damon were in town with their respective producers and Kim Norgaard arrived as ringmaster of the CNN coverage. Sometimes too much talent and egos battling to be on air can turn ugly, particularly if one reporter swoops down late in the game and â€˜bigfootsâ€™ the rest. But between the three of us, the dynamic was great as was the division of labor between the human toll story, newsgathering, and the investigation angle.</p><p>One of the women who died in the attack was a pregnant radio DJ. Victoria and I went to her funeral, in our private capacity. It was a Muslim funeral, at the Ismaili Mosque. Thousands of people had turned out to pay their respects. Everyone I met was in shock, trying to avoid looking at the tragic bump in her stomach, and processing terror close to home. Aria, our family hairdresser and friend, and her daughter Shivani were there and we were all moved to tears.</p><p>President Uhuru Kenyatta finally made a statement on TV that the siege was over. Minutes later I finished my last live, exhausted with no sleep for four days and walked to our van. The phone rang. It was State House, adding to information and clarifying details which Victoria and I wrote up and sent in to CNN wires.</p><p>After a strong drink, I finally drifted off to sleep for a few hours at a hotel in town. I vividly recall the image that night. I am sitting in a car leaving the crushed rooftop of Westgate one final time. In my hands are the only survivors that day from the mall. They are two Black Moor fish in a plastic bag filled urgently with water. They swim in circles, glancing at each other, eyewitnesses that will never tell.</p>','<p>The crunch of shattered glass beneath my feet, the bullet holes in windows and the acrid smell of disaster enveloped me the moment I entered my favorite mall in Nairobi. It was surreal. Days ago a massacre happened here as friends and family lived out a typical mundane errand and chatter filled Saturday morning.</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 18px; line-height: 34px;\">I felt hollow, paralyzed as the magnitude of the inane bloodshed and violence that occurred lay on a fractured canvas before me. I was dazed. A lump in my throat fought back insistent tears as I recalled numerous coffees at Art CafÃ©, endless ice-cream purchases at Nakumatt, banking with dad upstairs or sharing a strawberry frozen yogurt downstairs