organizational calm under fire, which was stabilizing to any talent. We analyzed all intelligence coming to CNN and decided what was news worthy, what could be backed up, and what could not.</p><p>Victoria quickly came to believe the strength of my sources on the ground. I would receive a text.</p><p>â€œAn explosion is about to happenâ€. Seconds later, it did.</p><p>â€œWear your helmet and flack jacket. Terrorists believed on the loose in your area.â€ Gunfire erupted almost immediately.</p><p>In moments, I felt I was in a really bad action movie. Our family friend Collette, a spa manager and owner on Peponi Road close to the mall, gave the whole CNN team access to bathrooms, shelter from rain, and the use of her kitchen for our planning and analysis â€˜war roomâ€™.</p><p>By now the team was much bigger, Nima el-Bagir and Arwa Damon were in town with their respective producers and Kim Norgaard arrived as ringmaster of the CNN coverage. Sometimes too much talent and egos battling to be on air can turn ugly, particularly if one reporter swoops down late in the game and â€˜bigfootsâ€™ the rest. But between the three of us, the dynamic was great as was the division of labor between the human toll story, newsgathering, and the investigation angle.</p><p>One of the women who died in the attack was a pregnant radio DJ. Victoria and I went to her funeral, in our private capacity. It was a Muslim funeral, at the Ismaili Mosque. Thousands of people had turned out to pay their respects. Everyone I met was in shock, trying to avoid looking at the tragic bump in her stomach, and processing terror close to home. Aria, our family hairdresser and friend, and her daughter Shivani were there and we were all moved to tears.</p><p>President Uhuru Kenyatta finally made a statement on TV that the siege was over. Minutes later I finished my last live, exhausted with no sleep for four days and walked to our van. The phone rang. It was State House, adding to information and clarifying details which Victoria and I wrote up and sent in to CNN wires.</p><p>After a strong drink, I finally drifted off to sleep for a few hours at a hotel in town. I vividly recall the image that night. I am sitting in a car leaving the crushed rooftop of Westgate one final time. In my hands are the only survivors that day from the mall. They are two Black Moor fish in a plastic bag filled urgently with water. They swim in circles, glancing at each other, eyewitnesses that will never tell.</p>','/content/images/2015/05/blackmoorfish.jpg',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<span style=\"font-family: Lato, helvetica, arial, san-serif; font-size: medium; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 16px;\">The crunch of shattered glass beneath my feet, the bullet holes in windows and the acrid smell of disaster enveloped me the moment I entered my favorite mall in Nairobi. It was surreal. Days ago a massacre happened here as friends and family lived out a typical mundane errand and chatter filled Saturday morning.</span>',3,'2015-05-09 19:06:45',2,'2015-06-05 01:34:59',2,'2015-05-09 19:06:58',2,0),(10,'43d783fe-9764-48ef-9dab-5ed5e3d15e2d','Rena','rena','<p>Rena</p><p>It was 1999 and I was hosting the mid morning show on Capital FM radio in Nairobi, anchoring the KTN news at night, and stringing for the BBC world service putting together more serious pieces. I had made a shift from entertainment only to hard news instantly when I saw the black smoke rise from the window on the nineteenth floor of Lohnro House in down town Nairobi on August 7, 1998.</p><p>The time was 10:38am. That was the moment the US embassy in Nairobi was attacked by terrorists. I was on the air. I remember how the building shook and how I thought it must be an earthquake. I remember watching a bearded American journalist for CNN reporting on the story a day later. His name was Jerrold Kessel. I never imagined I would one day be interviewing him on the air, as his anchor.</p><p>Months later at our home in Parklands, I was watching CNN one evening. I got it in my head â€œI can do that.â€ I tend to act quickly and relentlessly when I want something badly. Plus my dad always tells me to aim for the stars and even if I donâ€™t make it, and land on the moon, then thatâ€™s OK too! So thatâ€™s what I did.</p><p>My friend Salim Amin of Camerapix in Nairobi referred me to a lady called Maggie Eales in London to whom I sent a demo tape of me reading the evening news at KTN. She passed in on to a woman who changed my life. Rena Golden, the head of talent and programming at CNN International based in London.</p><p>Once I received Renaâ€™s email, I wouldnâ€™t stop sending notes. The first time she emailed me, she told me that I looked good on camera but I had no real journalism experience and that I was more of an academic from what she could tell from my CV.</p><p>I responded saying that was not the case and I had done some very serious journalism for BBC radio. I offered to send her some scripts I had written under the guidance of senior producers in London. One of them was a thirty minute script on the deregistration of NGOs after the US embassy bombing in Kenya.</p><p>Rena agreed and I sent her every intelligent script I had written. She went silent for a long time and I mustered up the gall to send her another note. There were more that went by with no response.</p><p>At the same time I had been planning a trip to the United States to see a young man I was dating. In a breakthrough email to Rena, I said I was â€œcoming to Atlanta anywayâ€ and could she â€œplease give me a screen test. â€œ My thinking was that I could use a piece of video with myself anchoring at CNN as part of another demo tape to send to another news organization. That was the best-case scenario for me professionally and personally I would have a wonderful time and spend a few days in Charleston and Savannah with my beau.</p><p>Rena replied saying something along these lines: â€œI am not hiring you, I will not give you a job, I will not pay for your ticket or your accommodation, but you can come if you want to and at your expense. I will give you a screen test.â€</p><p>I couldnâ€™t stop screaming with delight when I received that. I read every newspaper, every magazine I could, I watched the news on various channels, and then it came to the night before the trip. I had a crisis of confidence.</p><p>â€œWhy am I even bothering,â€ I cried to my mum, â€œsheâ€™s told me sheâ€™s not hiring me.â€</p><p>â€œJust go,â€ urged my mum. â€œDo it. Youâ€™ve come so farâ€</p><p>â€œBut itâ€™s a waste. Look how expensive this ticket is. Itâ€™s almost all my savings. Why am I even thinking I can do this? I donâ€™t even know what Iâ€™m doing. I canâ€™t do it.â€</p><p>â€œYes you can,â€ repeated mum over again. I doubted myself all night. I pulled myself together and then next day I caught the flight out from Jomo Kenyatta International Airport in Nairobi to Atlanta via Amsterdam.</p><p>At this point in my life I was feeling like a was a new person. I had suffered for many years from a skin disease called psoriasis, and survived an extreme form of its manifestation. My skin was exciting and clear for the first time in my young adult life and my mother had a beautiful strapless red dress made for me for when I met the man I was seeing for a lovely dinner. It was liberating to realize I could wear anything without stress or flakes of scales falling.</p><p>I will never forget walking though the red and blue exterior of the CNN building, the huge letters sitting outside and the park and parking deck around it. My palms sweated and my hands shook but my eyes sparkled with anticipation. I took at deep breath and asked for Rena Golden at the front desk.</p><p>Minutes later, she arrived, with a mane of black hair, a sharp suit no make up and a no nonsense attitude. She shook my hand briskly and whisked me up the escalator and left into the CNN International Newsroom.</p><p>I recall thinking how confident she was, I remember how she smiled at me reassuringly and how she communicated crisply and clearly. Rena walked me to the center of the newsroom and introduced me to Dan Williams, the head of writers, who was going to give me a general knowledge news quiz and also test my ability to â€œwrite news copy from news wires.â€ I had no idea what exactly that meant but I nodded and smiled nervously.</p><p>The quiz was basic and I handled it with ease. Then Dan gave me stories printed out from Reuters and the Associated Press and asked me to use that information to write the scripts that TV anchors read on air. I had never done this before but I managed to pull something off after about one hour.</p><p>Rena walked over and took me to a smaller studio. She told me she would ask me to read the prompter, conduct an interview and finally, handle a breaking news scenario. She said she would be â€œin my earâ€ meaning I would be able to hear her from an earpiece that I had just learned to wear.</p><p>Reading large white words rolling up a black screen was easy, though my mouth was dry. In the second go-around, the words suddenly disappeared as if someone had pressed delete. I looked down and picked up the sentence easily off the hard copy of paper scripts in front of me, and continued without missing a beat.</p><p>Next was a fake interview with the Israeli Prime Minster. Rena pretended to be him. She outlined the scenario and I asked a few basic questions to which she responded. I was no political expert, especially with the complexity of the Israeli â€“ Palestinian conflict, so I kept my questions very basic, common sense, and didnâ€™t try do any intellectual acrobatics.</p><p>Then it was time for breaking news. Jeff Marcowsky,a director in the CNN control room, had winked at me before I went into the studio and said â€œplane crashâ€. Brad Rhoads, a supervisor had also laughed about the same. I had my first inside tip.</p><p>Sure enough, Rena described the scene of a plane crash and asked me to do an interview with a reporter on the scene and to ad-lib about the crash. It was hard but I was having a fun once I settled into it and my adrenalin was racing.</p><p>At the end of the screen test she came in and asked â€œhow long are you here for?â€</p><p>â€œA couple more hours,â€ I said.</p><p>â€œCome and see me before you leaveâ€</p><p>â€œDonâ€™t forget a copy of the screen test on tape,â€ I reminded her.</p><p>In the time I was there I met with three additional players at CNN at the time, Riz Khan, an anchor of the famous Q&amp;A talk show. Riz was extremely warm and very funny. Steve Cassidy and Parisa Khosravi on the international desk, the heartbeat of a news operation that gathers the news, each met and talked to me. I asked many questions hoping that I would learn as much as possible in the little time I was going to be at CNN.</p><p>When it was it was time to leave, I went to see Rena to say goodbye and get my tape.</p><p>â€œWhy donâ€™t you come in for a chatâ€ she said. I entered her corner office and sat down across from her in a comfortable black chair.</p><p>â€œWhat nationality are you,?â€ she asked.</p><p>â€œKenyan,â€ I responded.</p><p>I will never ever forget the next lines she said to me. Till this day, it is one of the highlights of my life.</p><p>â€œIâ€™m going to do something Iâ€™ve never done before. Iâ€™m going to offer you a job right now. I know where you have been the past few hours, I know who you have met with. I like how persistent youâ€™ve been. Thatâ€™s that kind of person I want at CNN.â€</p><p>I stared at her, slowly beginning to understand what she was saying.</p><p>â€œWhat?â€</p><p>She smiled. â€œYou donâ€™t have to respond right now. Take some time to think about it.â€</p><p>â€œYes!â€ I said. â€œI accept!â€ I wanted to jump up and down like crazy.</p><p>â€œI will hire you as a writer/producerâ€ she said. â€œWe will teach you the basic building blocks of television news. Iâ€™ll give you anchoring opportunities and if you do well I will promote you as a full time anchor. If not, you can continue to write and produce in the newsroom and then return to Kenya after that.â€</p><p>It was incredible. I went to the hotel I was staying at, the Marriot Marquis in downtown Atlanta, and called home. My parents didnâ€™t quite believe me at first. My father cried. We were all in total shock.</p><p>I returned to Kenya a week later, and played the song â€œMidnight Train to Georgiaâ€ by Gladys Knight every day on my mid-morning radio show on 94.4 Capital FM, and no one could figure out why I suddenly loved it so much.</p>','<p>Rena</p><p>It was 1999 and I was hosting the mid morning show on Capital FM radio in Nairobi, anchoring the KTN news at night, and stringing for the BBC world service putting together more serious pieces. I had made a shift from entertainment only to hard news instantly when I saw the black smoke rise from the window on the nineteenth floor of Lohnro House in down town Nairobi on August 7, 1998.</p><p>The time was 10:38am. That was the moment the US embassy in Nairobi was attacked by terrorists. I was on the air. I remember how the building shook and how I thought it must be an earthquake. I remember watching a bearded American journalist for CNN reporting on the story a day later. His name was Jerrold Kessel. I never imagined I would one day be interviewing him on the air, as his anchor.</p><p>Months later at our home in Parklands, I was watching CNN one evening. I got it in my head â€œI can do that.â€ I tend to act quickly and relentlessly when I want something badly. Plus my dad always tells me to aim for the stars and even if I donâ€™t make it, and land on the moon, then thatâ€™s OK too! So thatâ€™s what I did.</p><p>My friend Salim Amin of Camerapix in Nairobi referred me to a lady called Maggie Eales in London to whom I sent a demo tape of me reading the evening news at KTN. She passed in on to a woman who changed my