layers at CNN at the time, Riz Khan, an anchor of the famous Q&amp;A talk show. Riz was extremely warm and very funny. Steve Cassidy and Parisa Khosravi on the international desk, the heartbeat of a news operation that gathers the news, each met and talked to me. I asked many questions hoping that I would learn as much as possible in the little time I was going to be at CNN.</p><p>When it was it was time to leave, I went to see Rena to say goodbye and get my tape.</p><p>â€œWhy donâ€™t you come in for a chatâ€ she said. I entered her corner office and sat down across from her in a comfortable black chair.</p><p>â€œWhat nationality are you,?â€ she asked.</p><p>â€œKenyan,â€ I responded.</p><p>I will never ever forget the next lines she said to me. Till this day, it is one of the highlights of my life.</p><p>â€œIâ€™m going to do something Iâ€™ve never done before. Iâ€™m going to offer you a job right now. I know where you have been the past few hours, I know who you have met with. I like how persistent youâ€™ve been. Thatâ€™s that kind of person I want at CNN.â€</p><p>I stared at her, slowly beginning to understand what she was saying.</p><p>â€œWhat?â€</p><p>She smiled. â€œYou donâ€™t have to respond right now. Take some time to think about it.â€</p><p>â€œYes!â€ I said. â€œI accept!â€ I wanted to jump up and down like crazy.</p><p>â€œI will hire you as a writer/producerâ€ she said. â€œWe will teach you the basic building blocks of television news. Iâ€™ll give you anchoring opportunities and if you do well I will promote you as a full time anchor. If not, you can continue to write and produce in the newsroom and then return to Kenya after that.â€</p><p>It was incredible. I went to the hotel I was staying at, the Marriot Marquis in downtown Atlanta, and called home. My parents didnâ€™t quite believe me at first. My father cried. We were all in total shock.</p><p>I returned to Kenya a week later, and played the song â€œMidnight Train to Georgiaâ€ by Gladys Knight every day on my mid-morning radio show on 94.4 Capital FM, and no one could figure out why I suddenly loved it so much.</p>','/content/images/2015/05/CNN_logo.jpg',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<span style=\"color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">â€œI am not hiring you, I will not give you a job, I will not pay for your ticket or your accommodation, but you can come if you want to and at your expense. I will give you a screen test.â€ Words spoken by the woman that changed my life.</span>',3,'2015-05-09 19:12:20',2,'2015-06-05 03:41:15',2,'2015-05-09 19:13:08',2,0),(11,'35ee9565-45d4-42f7-ac66-a4684a542b67','A Tale of Two Grandmas','a-tale-of-two-grandmas','<p>I believe in passion. I believe in purpose. I believe in following a dream fearlessly.</p><p>he year was 1974 and dusk had fallen in Kisumu, a town on the edge of lake victoria in Kenya. A family tragedy struck like a bolt of lighting. My grandfather Kassamali, and grandmother, Shirin, were entering their home at 8pm, returning from the mosque.</p><p>A lone guard, askari, stood in the parking lot adjacent to the entrance. Kassamali moved towards the guard asking what the matter was. The guard lunged towards him with a knife and stabbed him. Shirin had her hands slashed with a sharp blade, called a panga. She tried to help her husband but he bled to death. The killer was never found. The family believed it was motivated by a conflict over the Embassy Hotel Kassamali owned in Kisumu.</p><p>All five children of their children were devastated and the family fractured. The two sons fled to Canada, fearful they could be targeted in the dispute. My mother, Yasmin, the closest to my grandfather and the favorite, drove from Kisumu to Nairobi for the shocking funeral.</p><p>I had just been born that year, and never knew my grandfather, though Iâ€™m told he was a gentle and religious man. In a traditional Indian arranged marriage, he married my grandmother when she was twelve years old</p><p>She didnâ€™t even have her period. Shirin had a tough life from an early age. She was poorly treated by her stepmother and equally mistreated by her mother-in-law. Shirin had five children and ran the household in Kisumu. When her husband started the struggle with his general store business and lost confidence, she stepped in and made deals with suppliers and structured the business and enabled the economic survival of her family.</p><p>After his death, she liquidated the businesses and left for Toronto, Canada. The funds she had asked a relative to remit, so she could survive in Canada, were never sent to her.</p><p>Shirin didnâ€™t give up, and she was too proud to live off her sons. Her two married daughters were also in Toronto and she didnâ€™t want to be a burden. She loved into a studio apartment alone, and got a job washing dishes in a hotel. She learned how to shop of groceries. She barely spoke English, and taught herself to do so over the years.</p><p>My Nanima (small mother, as we called our motherâ€™s mother) learned how to take the bus and withstand brutally cold Canadian winters. Shirin became hardened, strong-minded, opinionated, and came to rely only on herself. Her joys were Indian movies, meditation and prayer, travel with her hard earned and saved money around the world with her group of grandmas, and her grandchildren who lived nearby.</p><p>Coming from an environment where house help and labor was plentiful, it was a massive cultural and social adjustment.</p><p>I lived with her for a few weeks, when I was in Canada attending McGill and York university. She gave me spending money, money for steroid medication for my skin disease, psoriasis when I didnâ€™t have any, and didnâ€™t get too angry with me when she found a packet of cigarettes hidden in my bag.</p><p>â€œThis is not right,â€ she said, â€œitâ€™s bad for your healthâ€</p><p>â€œPlease donâ€™t tell mum,â€ was my desperate response.</p><p>â€œI wonâ€™t but stop it.â€</p><p>She remained economically independent and strong willed until she passed away in 2009 in Toronto.</p><p>No matter how tough things got, she would say to all of us â€œDonâ€™t worry, be happy,â€ somehow loving and internalizing the 1988 cappella hit song by Bobby McFerrin. This is how I remember her.</p><p>My dadâ€™s mum, Daulat Khanu loved Boy Georgeâ€™s Karma Chameleon. I recall her dancing in a pink Indian Sari and singing with me at our old house in Gigiri, Nairobi.</p><p>â€œIâ€™m amazed my one thing about you,â€ she said to me in Guajarati, the Indian dialect we spoke to both our grandmothers in.</p><p>â€œWhat?â€ I laughed dancing around, please that I just got the new â€˜Now thatâ€™s what I called musicâ€™, cassette tape from London.</p><p>â€œThat you can remember all the words to so many songs.â€ Itâ€™s true. I do have an uncanny memory for lyrics of songs I hear.</p><p>I was the closest of all grand children to Ma. I felt connected to her. She was a gentle spirit and cared for even the animals that lived around us.</p><p>She would feed sugar to the ants at home.</p><p>â€œWhat are you doing?â€ my father recalled asking her, startled at all the white lines in the garden.</p><p>â€œEven the ants have to eat,â€ she said, â€œwhoâ€™s going to feed them.</p><p>She ordered prime meats for both Tommy the stray dog and mince for all the stray cats who I remember would turn up sharp at half past twelve for lunch daily.</p><p>Ma brought grocery items from old Kenyan women who would come to our gate with baskets of fresh vegetables and fruits.</p><p>She was born in a small town called Machakos in Kenya in 1920, the eldest of four children. Her family ran a laundry store in town and were relatively poor. She too had an arranged marriage to Remtuallah Verjee, my grandfather, a prominent man in Nairobi at the time.</p><p>She liked to dress both in Indian attire as well as English ladies dresses, with gloves and hats. She played rummy and bridge with friends on entertained a lot at home. Her life revolved around my grandfather and when he died in 1982, she lots her sense of purpose and joie de vivre, and suffered from depression and eventually a stroke.</p><p>I often think of Ma and Nanima and wonder what they would have thought of what I have done and become. I see Ma sitting near our grey old-fashioned telephone, on a dark brown chair, in a blue and white dressing gown, her hair in a bun, talking to her two close friends and laughing hard until her body shakes.</p><p>I see Nanima, cooking and softly singing to herself in her small cluttered apartment, watching the weather channel clock and making sure she was always on time.</p><p>My grandmothers combined taught me how to be tough, self reliant, to embrace Indian culture and at the same and to be gentle and compassionate in spirit.</p>','<p>I believe in passion. I believe in purpose. I believe in following a dream fearlessly.</p><p>he year was 1974 and dusk had fallen in Kisumu, a town on the edge of lake victoria in Kenya. A family tragedy struck like a bolt of lighting. My grandfather Kassamali, and grandmother, Shirin, were entering their home at 8pm, returning from the mosque.</p><p>A lone guard, askari, stood in the parking lot adjacent to the entrance. Kassamali moved towards the guard asking what the matter was. The guard lunged towards him with a knife and stabbed him. Shirin had her hands slashed with a sharp blade, called a panga. She tried to help her husband but he bled to death. The killer was never found. The family believed it was motivated by a conflict over the Embassy Hotel Kassamali owned in Kisumu.</p><p>All five children of their children were devastated and the family fractured. The two sons fled to Canada, fearful they could be targeted in the dispute. My mother, Yasmin, the closest to my grandfather and the favorite, drove from Kisumu to Nairobi for the shocking funeral.</p><p>I had just been born that year, and never knew my grandfather, though Iâ€™m told he was a gentle and religious man. In a traditional Indian arranged marriage, he married my grandmother when she was twelve years old</p><p>She didnâ€™t even have her period. Shirin had a tough life from an early age. She was poorly treated by her stepmother and equally mistreated by her mother-in-law. Shirin had five children and ran the household in Kisumu. When her husband started the struggle with his general store business and lost confidence, she stepped in and made deals with suppliers and structured the business and enabled the economic survival of her family.</p><p>After his death, she liquidated the businesses and left for Toronto, Canada. The funds she had asked a relative to remit, so she could survive in Canada, were never sent to her.</p><p>Shirin didnâ€™t give up, and she was too proud to live off her sons. Her two married daughters were also in Toronto and she didnâ€™t want to be a burden. She loved into a studio apartment alone, and got a job washing dishes in a hotel. She learned how to shop of groceries. She barely spoke English, and taught herself to do so over the years.</p><p>My Nanima (small mother, as we called our motherâ€™s mother) learned how to take the bus and withstand brutally cold Canadian winters. Shirin became hardened, strong-minded, opinionated, and came to rely only on herself. Her joys were Indian movies, meditation and prayer, travel with her hard earned and saved money around the world with her group of grandmas, and her grandchildren who lived nearby.</p><p>Coming from an environment where house help and labor was plentiful, it was a massive cultural and social adjustment.</p><p>I lived with her for a few weeks, when I was in Canada attending McGill and York university. She gave me spending money, money for steroid medication for my skin disease, psoriasis when I didnâ€™t have any, and didnâ€™t get too angry with me when she found a packet of cigarettes hidden in my bag.</p><p>â€œThis is not right,â€ she said, â€œitâ€™s bad for your healthâ€</p><p>â€œPlease donâ€™t tell mum,â€ was my desperate response.</p><p>â€œI wonâ€™t but stop it.â€</p><p>She remained economically independent and strong willed until she passed away in 2009 in Toronto.</p><p>No matter how tough things got, she would say to all of us â€œDonâ€™t worry, be happy,â€ somehow loving and internalizing the 1988 cappella hit song by Bobby McFerrin. This is how I remember her.</p><p>My dadâ€™s mum, Daulat Khanu loved Boy Georgeâ€™s Karma Chameleon. I recall her dancing in a pink Indian Sari and singing with me at our old house in Gigiri, Nairobi.</p><p>â€œIâ€™m amazed my one thing about you,â€ she said to me in Guajarati, the Indian dialect we spoke to both our grandmothers in.</p><p>â€œWhat?â€ I laughed dancing around, please that I just got the new â€˜Now thatâ€™s what I called musicâ€™, cassette tape from London.</p><p>â€œThat you can remember all the words to so many songs.â€ Itâ€™s true. I do have an uncanny memory for lyrics of songs I hear.</p><p>I was the closest of all grand children to Ma. I felt connected to her. She was a gentle spirit and cared for even the animals that lived around us.</p><p>She would feed sugar to the ants at home.</p><p>â€œWhat are you doing?â€ my father recalled asking her, startled at all the white lines in the garden.</p><p>â€œEven the ants have to eat,â€ she said, â€œwhoâ€™s going to feed them.</p><p>She ordered prime meats for both Tommy the stray dog and mince for all the stray cats who I remember would turn up sharp at half past twelve for lunch daily.</p><p>Ma brought grocery items from old Kenyan women who would come to our gate with baskets of fresh vegetables and fruits.</p><p>She was born in a small town called Machakos in Kenya in 1920, the eldest of four children. Her family ran a laundry store in town and were relatively poor. She too had an arranged marriage to Remtuallah Verjee, my grandfather, a prominent man in Nairobi at the time.</p><p>She liked to dress both in Indian attire as well as English ladies dresses, with gloves and hats. She played rummy and bridge with friends on entertained a lot at home. Her life revolved around my grandfather and when he died in 1982, she lots her sense of purpose and joie de vivre, and suffered from depression and eventually a stroke.</p><p>I often think of Ma and Nanima and wonder what they would have thought of what I have done and become. I see Ma sitting near our grey old-fashioned telephone, on a dark brown chair, in a blue and white dressing gown, her hair in a bun, talking to her two close friends and laughing hard until her body shakes.</p><p>I see Nanima, cooking and softly singing to herself in her small cluttered apartment, watching the weather channel clock and making sure she was always on time.</p><p>My grandmothers combined taught me how to be tough, self reliant, to embrace Indian culture and at the same and to be gentle and compassionate in spirit.</p>','/content/images/2015/05/BONIFACE_MWANGI82.JPG',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<span style=\"color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">My grandmothers combined taught me how to be tough, self reliant, to embrace Indian culture and at the same and to be gentle and compassionate in spirit.</span>',3,'2015-05-09 19:15:09',2,'2015-06-05 03:41:15',2,'2015-05-09 19:15:23',2,0),(12,'84ce84a0-3c31-4e8f-9b66-0f43d92c92b9','Corvus','corvus','<p>Victory was lonely for detective Lucy Onyango. &nbsp;The case breakthrough brought with it blinding flashlights, press conferences searching for a slick sound bite and a high profile award ceremony. &nbsp;Her star status demanded she be there, the smart glamorous and powerful symbol for Kenyan justice. &nbsp;But she was a no show for the dog and pony show. Every cellular device beeped and pinged her, until she removed the batteries to silence them.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She had earned this down time and no one was going to drag her out of the ritualized way she needed to spend it. &nbsp;Not the Police Commissioner himself, not the media hounds, not her own sense of duty. &nbsp;The vicious case was over and Lucy needed to self-inflict â€˜pauseâ€™ and â€˜muteâ€™ while Nairobi churned ahead in a fast forward frenzy.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Alone in her darkened room, the drapes drawn, and windows pulled in, she tried to forget. &nbsp;She remained numb for hours under the covers until it wore off and her demon, Feeling, returned. No matter how hard she attempted to block its surge, it rose like bile, her chest would ache, she would double over and the tears would gather to the edge of her lids but never cascade down her face. &nbsp;The walls would witness only her silent screaming. &nbsp;The self-imposed solitary confinement would last days, sometimes weeks.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;The moment she solved a case was naturally exhilarating and satisfying. But it was short-lived because her past always sabotaged her present. She would see history and bad choices thundering like a freight train in the night, carrying a cargo of blame, to hit her as she lay on railway tracks waiting for the headlines lights to inevitably come closer. Guilt and regret mingled in those moments, hate and pain that had been filed away years after it happened resurfaced, and Lucy couldnâ€™t bear her self. â€œMercyâ€, she whispered repeatedly.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;This case was particularly tough because young boys and girls had been the targets because they were white, too white. East African albinos in this region were coveted. Old wives tales that albino body parts held rare supernatural power were still believed, so dozens of children were kidnapped, trafficked between Kenya and Tanzania and killed. &nbsp;Her informants had come through, the sting operation had been successful and Lucy had nailed the perpetrators. &nbsp;They would face justice.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Lucy lifted her tall sinewy body from her bed and stumbled out of the room, over her clothes, her gun, notebooks strewn on the floor, into the living room. She caught sight of herself in the mirror, exhausted red-rimmed eyes, her short hair stuck out in all directions exposing the small gold hoop earrings she had forgotten to remove. &nbsp;She had thick lips and large almond shaped eyes, the color of which was onyx black and fierce, and could bore a hole into anyone during an interrogation. &nbsp;Lucy stood in her white bra and underwear only. &nbsp;Her tattoo on her back, between her shoulder blades, was visible, two diamond shapes, on their sides and clasped together, representing handcuffs for offenders of the law. &nbsp;It was an old African folk symbol of law and justice.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She was about to break it. &nbsp;Lucy opened the sliding door of her flat in the South B area of Nairobi, and stepped onto the balcony, bending over to rummage inside a plant. She pulled out a clear plastic bag from the dirt. &nbsp;What she did alone in her own space was her business, she just had to be careful or she would lose her position as the ranking female detective in the country, DCIO of Ongata Rongai police station.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She would only turn to marijuana when she sank so deep into herself that she needed to block it all out. The flash of the body, in the ditch, another cut to pieces, the bleeding, the eyes, their lifelessness and their hopelessness in the last moments on earth. &nbsp;Their loved ones would try to understand this level of brutality for the rest of their lives, wrestle with the courts, confront corruption, and incompetence. &nbsp;It would destroy some, and breathe passion into others, championing causes, seeking change, perhaps even starting a foundation, yet none of that would ever fill the hole. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œMercy,â€ she whispered as she lit up a tightly packed joint, closing her eyes, and throwing her head back in relief and allowing herself the cushion comfort of the smoke enveloping her. It was a relief. Thank goodness Alan, her boyfriend, was up country in Kiambu dealing with a sick aunt, and out of her way. He was a good man, he loved her, was loyal and rare. She didnâ€™t know another Kenyan man who would be willing to do mundane household chores, and conduct a business on the sidelines.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Lately though, she had to push away a gnawing irritation with him. &nbsp;It seemed unfair because he was loving and thoughtful. &nbsp;He wanted their relationship formalized with his Kikuyu family and her Luo one, two opposing tribes. &nbsp;Modern Kenya was fine with that, a Kariuki-Onyango marriage, but is that what she wanted? It seemed like the right, and natural step to take after two years. &nbsp;Alan wanted a child soon, but she was resistant. She wasnâ€™t sure she wanted to bring a child into the violent and hateful world she was immersed in. &nbsp;Plus her new position was demanding, even with her unusual ability to recall sounds, images and small objects clearly. &nbsp;An eidetic memory was what the doctor at Nairobi hospital had called it. Right now she was so foggy, she couldnâ€™t remember.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œLucy!â€ she heard someone shout, accompanied by a loud bang on the door. &nbsp;She jumped at the thud. &nbsp;She ignored in and inhaled the joint again slowly, holding it delicately between her right thumb and forefinger.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œOpen up! Itâ€™s Peter.â€ &nbsp;She shook her head. &nbsp;Peter Karanja was her number two, waiting to stab her in the back any time he could. He coveted the promotion she received, and was bitter when, after twenty years of service, he didnâ€™t get it. He was an old school, old hand, sexist pig that was unable to come to terms with taking orders from a younger female officer. This was his perfect opportunity to report on her and she was too stoned to cover up her current state. She had been explicit that morning, and Peter knew she would be out of the mix for a while, like the cases before. &nbsp;He should relish being in charge for once, not be banging down her door. &nbsp;â€œDetective!â€ he kept calling out relentlessly.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She didnâ€™t answer and he eventually gave up. She knew he would be back. Something serious must have happened. Lucy reached into her pocket and turned on her mobile phone. Instantly, the double beeps flooded in making her flinch. Her tongue felt thick, like cotton wool, her mouth was dry and her eyes pleasantly glazed. &nbsp;She closed them, and took herself back for a split second to the lake where she had felt the freest and happiest in her life, playing with her sister and eating tilapia fish. &nbsp;Lucy looked at her messages and broke out in a sweat.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Unsteady on her feet, she grasped the battered family furniture, the sparse white walls, banged her knee on the stained coffee table and turned on a cold shower. Lucy closed her eyes, threw her head back letting the needle like droplets pierce her chiseled face. &nbsp;Her body finally gave in, her shoulders heaved, she gasped and her body convulsed. &nbsp;The tears flowed for more than an hour. The release was the same each time and left her on her knees, forehead prostrated on the floor, watching the water circle lazily in slow rippled motions, taking their time before aimlessly sinking down the drain.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; She needed to focus quickly. Naked, Lucy grabbed a thick slab of bread in the kitchen, added butter and strawberry jam, and made a hot cup of milky tea. &nbsp;She ate and drank it in her room, while dressing. &nbsp; Lucy was stylish, though conservative in her dress. &nbsp;She wore the same outfit each day, no-nonsense, but still sexy and feminine: A narrow blue skirt that showed off her killer legs, crisp white shirt that exposed enough skin to display a sentimental silver necklace, and low heeled black shoes. &nbsp;She was five foot seven, and didnâ€™t need to tower over her already intimidated male counterparts. &nbsp;She grabbed her gun, made sure it was loaded and packed it in behind her skirt, pulling on her well-fitting blue blazer.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œBoss!â€ She could hear the sarcasm in his voice, as Peter turned up again rapping at her door. &nbsp;She flung it open, already annoyed.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œI know, I saw the messages,â€ she snapped, noticing he was observing her carefully. &nbsp;She picked up her black purse, and thrust a few new note pads in. &nbsp;â€œIâ€™m on my way.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œForensics is headed there now,â€ said Peter</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œGood.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œWe have a name.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œWho?â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œDaniel Drake.â€ Lucy stopped at the doorway and stared at him, various images and sounds of the man she had seen on TV funneling down through her mind at lightning speed.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œWhat? â€œ Drake was one of the most powerful businessmen in Kenya and Chairman and CEO of Raven International. â€œAre you sure?â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œThe boss wants you on the case personally given the victim,â€ he said with thick traces of bitterness in his voice, referring to the Police Commissioner.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œIâ€™ll meet you there,â€ she said curtly walking out. â€œAskari,â€ she called out in Swahili to the guard who opened the white grilled gates to her detached home. Lucy reversed out in her white Toyota station wagon looking at the cream walls and brown rims of her middle class estate. She sped towards the Langata suburb, jockeying with the famous number 11 mini buses, called matatus, the main public transport in the area.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She passed the Mariakani Cottage hospital, glanced in the rearview mirror noticing Peter keeping up with her, as they made their way to the crime scene at Nairobiâ€™s famous Ngâ€™ong racecourse. Traffic on a Sunday would be horrendous, even with her siren blaring on the rooftop.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She reached Dagoretti corner and weaved through cars loaded with families looking to spend the afternoon at the Junction Mall no doubt at the KFC that has recently opened up there. She leaned out of her window and ordered a group of â€˜chokorasâ€™, street boys who looked up to no good and likely high on glue, out of the way. Lucy took in the hyper detail of her environment. She swerved around and cursed at a matatu that refused to give way to her. Matatu names were memorable and she noted this one when she had more time to reprimand the driver. It was called â€˜XYZâ€™, after a popular Kenyan satirical cartoon show.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;The â€˜Jua Kaliâ€™ industry was in full swing. It literally translated to the â€˜hot sunâ€™ and meant that these goods and services on the streets operated outside the formal business sector of the city. &nbsp;The trade was roaring as always, flowerpots and funeral stones, sand and soapstone furniture and fashionable second hand clothes, lined up on the dirty sidewalks. Lingala music from Congo blasted from old-fashioned radios and men and women sat under trees drinking Vimto or Fanta sodas swapping gossip or complaining about the endless spates of political dramas, as they waited for potential customers.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Water tankers were parked haphazardly next to each other with â€˜soft waterâ€™ painted carefully on both sides. &nbsp;There was a water shortage in the city recently, and many were desperate just to bathe. She saw large drums of water being loaded onto the back of a pick up truck likely to pour into a water tank. &nbsp;Dozens of people carried small yellow jerry cans of water too. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œYes,â€ said Lucy picking up her phone?</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œItâ€™s forensics. We are here and ready to enter.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œGo in.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œYes detective.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œIâ€™ll be there in a few minutes and will need access. I want a set of plastic gloves and shoes ready.â€&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œWeâ€™ve set up a tent outside already and the police have the cordon.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Lucy took a deep breath as she turned onto the slip road leading to the racecourse. â€No one leaves without my permission,â€ she said to the guard at the gate, noticing the throngs of people standing under the trees.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;This was going to be her most high profile case, as the worst possible time for her. &nbsp;She had to be on her A-game. So did the men plotting just a few miles away.</p><p><br></p><p><b>Chapter 2: The Hunters</b></p><p>&nbsp;Somewhere in Nairobi the small room glowed with the blue neon light from monitors and the claustrophobic reflections it threw in the small shadowy room. The five men inside preferred it this way; always nighttime so there was less chance of discovery. They were fierce in their focus technically savvy, arrogant about their capabilities and exceptionally greedy. This one mission was going to deliver more money than they would see in a lifetime of slogging but the danger, and the stakes were high.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;There was no margin for error inside this pod where technology was the most lethal and the most spectacular. Each had accepted there would be no contact with any one in the outside world for fear of slipping up, sending a signal that could lead to discovery and disaster.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Each had proven their mental strength and almost warped ability to block out the world of lattes, bills, cafes and movies, to stifle emotion and desire, and refusal to trust, except perhaps, each other. They were in it together, embracing a life of falsehoods that hid behind the shattered tapestry of their own lives.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;They tolerated the tight dirty brown cubicles, the cold coffees, overflowing ashtrays, crushed soda cans and stale pizza, the daily dinner, always frozen and stocked up for the week. Tense faces and urgent voices rose suddenly breaking the bleary-eyed methodical typing and mapping.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œTo the left moreâ€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œI canâ€™t keep up, sheâ€™s moving faster.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œJust step on it will you.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œSheâ€™s changing course, good, slowing down. Here we go.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œThere!â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œPut a lock on it.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;All eyes were glued to the largest monitor in the room. They had their prey in sight and she was beautiful, waiting to be taken.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œThe boss will be pleased.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œItâ€™s taken long enough.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œThe bird had a problem. It took time to fix.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œDonâ€™t let it happen again.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œRight.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œSheâ€™s pretty spectacular.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œGet back to work boys. This is just the beginning of hard days ahead. This is what weâ€™ve been working towards.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;From now on, whatever maneuvers the target made, however unexpected or clever, Master Control was watching for that inevitable moment of weakness, waiting for a mistake and it would happen soon. All that was needed was the agreed upon order from the man calling the shots. He had</p>','<p>Victory was lonely for detective Lucy Onyango. &nbsp;The case breakthrough brought with it blinding flashlights, press conferences searc