lives, wrestle with the courts, confront corruption, and incompetence. &nbsp;It would destroy some, and breathe passion into others, championing causes, seeking change, perhaps even starting a foundation, yet none of that would ever fill the hole. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œMercy,â€ she whispered as she lit up a tightly packed joint, closing her eyes, and throwing her head back in relief and allowing herself the cushion comfort of the smoke enveloping her. It was a relief. Thank goodness Alan, her boyfriend, was up country in Kiambu dealing with a sick aunt, and out of her way. He was a good man, he loved her, was loyal and rare. She didnâ€™t know another Kenyan man who would be willing to do mundane household chores, and conduct a business on the sidelines.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Lately though, she had to push away a gnawing irritation with him. &nbsp;It seemed unfair because he was loving and thoughtful. &nbsp;He wanted their relationship formalized with his Kikuyu family and her Luo one, two opposing tribes. &nbsp;Modern Kenya was fine with that, a Kariuki-Onyango marriage, but is that what she wanted? It seemed like the right, and natural step to take after two years. &nbsp;Alan wanted a child soon, but she was resistant. She wasnâ€™t sure she wanted to bring a child into the violent and hateful world she was immersed in. &nbsp;Plus her new position was demanding, even with her unusual ability to recall sounds, images and small objects clearly. &nbsp;An eidetic memory was what the doctor at Nairobi hospital had called it. Right now she was so foggy, she couldnâ€™t remember.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œLucy!â€ she heard someone shout, accompanied by a loud bang on the door. &nbsp;She jumped at the thud. &nbsp;She ignored in and inhaled the joint again slowly, holding it delicately between her right thumb and forefinger.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œOpen up! Itâ€™s Peter.â€ &nbsp;She shook her head. &nbsp;Peter Karanja was her number two, waiting to stab her in the back any time he could. He coveted the promotion she received, and was bitter when, after twenty years of service, he didnâ€™t get it. He was an old school, old hand, sexist pig that was unable to come to terms with taking orders from a younger female officer. This was his perfect opportunity to report on her and she was too stoned to cover up her current state. She had been explicit that morning, and Peter knew she would be out of the mix for a while, like the cases before. &nbsp;He should relish being in charge for once, not be banging down her door. &nbsp;â€œDetective!â€ he kept calling out relentlessly.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She didnâ€™t answer and he eventually gave up. She knew he would be back. Something serious must have happened. Lucy reached into her pocket and turned on her mobile phone. Instantly, the double beeps flooded in making her flinch. Her tongue felt thick, like cotton wool, her mouth was dry and her eyes pleasantly glazed. &nbsp;She closed them, and took herself back for a split second to the lake where she had felt the freest and happiest in her life, playing with her sister and eating tilapia fish. &nbsp;Lucy looked at her messages and broke out in a sweat.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Unsteady on her feet, she grasped the battered family furniture, the sparse white walls, banged her knee on the stained coffee table and turned on a cold shower. Lucy closed her eyes, threw her head back letting the needle like droplets pierce her chiseled face. &nbsp;Her body finally gave in, her shoulders heaved, she gasped and her body convulsed. &nbsp;The tears flowed for more than an hour. The release was the same each time and left her on her knees, forehead prostrated on the floor, watching the water circle lazily in slow rippled motions, taking their time before aimlessly sinking down the drain.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; She needed to focus quickly. Naked, Lucy grabbed a thick slab of bread in the kitchen, added butter and strawberry jam, and made a hot cup of milky tea. &nbsp;She ate and drank it in her room, while dressing. &nbsp; Lucy was stylish, though conservative in her dress. &nbsp;She wore the same outfit each day, no-nonsense, but still sexy and feminine: A narrow blue skirt that showed off her killer legs, crisp white shirt that exposed enough skin to display a sentimental silver necklace, and low heeled black shoes. &nbsp;She was five foot seven, and didnâ€™t need to tower over her already intimidated male counterparts. &nbsp;She grabbed her gun, made sure it was loaded and packed it in behind her skirt, pulling on her well-fitting blue blazer.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œBoss!â€ She could hear the sarcasm in his voice, as Peter turned up again rapping at her door. &nbsp;She flung it open, already annoyed.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œI know, I saw the messages,â€ she snapped, noticing he was observing her carefully. &nbsp;She picked up her black purse, and thrust a few new note pads in. &nbsp;â€œIâ€™m on my way.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œForensics is headed there now,â€ said Peter</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œGood.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œWe have a name.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œWho?â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œDaniel Drake.â€ Lucy stopped at the doorway and stared at him, various images and sounds of the man she had seen on TV funneling down through her mind at lightning speed.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œWhat? â€œ Drake was one of the most powerful businessmen in Kenya and Chairman and CEO of Raven International. â€œAre you sure?â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œThe boss wants you on the case personally given the victim,â€ he said with thick traces of bitterness in his voice, referring to the Police Commissioner.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œIâ€™ll meet you there,â€ she said curtly walking out. â€œAskari,â€ she called out in Swahili to the guard who opened the white grilled gates to her detached home. Lucy reversed out in her white Toyota station wagon looking at the cream walls and brown rims of her middle class estate. She sped towards the Langata suburb, jockeying with the famous number 11 mini buses, called matatus, the main public transport in the area.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She passed the Mariakani Cottage hospital, glanced in the rearview mirror noticing Peter keeping up with her, as they made their way to the crime scene at Nairobiâ€™s famous Ngâ€™ong racecourse. Traffic on a Sunday would be horrendous, even with her siren blaring on the rooftop.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;She reached Dagoretti corner and weaved through cars loaded with families looking to spend the afternoon at the Junction Mall no doubt at the KFC that has recently opened up there. She leaned out of her window and ordered a group of â€˜chokorasâ€™, street boys who looked up to no good and likely high on glue, out of the way. Lucy took in the hyper detail of her environment. She swerved around and cursed at a matatu that refused to give way to her. Matatu names were memorable and she noted this one when she had more time to reprimand the driver. It was called â€˜XYZâ€™, after a popular Kenyan satirical cartoon show.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;The â€˜Jua Kaliâ€™ industry was in full swing. It literally translated to the â€˜hot sunâ€™ and meant that these goods and services on the streets operated outside the formal business sector of the city. &nbsp;The trade was roaring as always, flowerpots and funeral stones, sand and soapstone furniture and fashionable second hand clothes, lined up on the dirty sidewalks. Lingala music from Congo blasted from old-fashioned radios and men and women sat under trees drinking Vimto or Fanta sodas swapping gossip or complaining about the endless spates of political dramas, as they waited for potential customers.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp;Water tankers were parked haphazardly next to each other with â€˜soft waterâ€™ painted carefully on both sides. &nbsp;There was a water shortage in the city recently, and many were desperate just to bathe. She saw large drums of water being loaded onto the back of a pick up truck likely to pour into a water tank. &nbsp;Dozens of people carried small yellow jerry cans of water too. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œYes,â€ said Lucy picking up her phone?</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œItâ€™s forensics. We are here and ready to enter.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œGo in.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œYes detective.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œIâ€™ll be there in a few minutes and will need access. I want a set of plastic gloves and shoes ready.â€&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œWeâ€™ve set up a tent outside already and the police have the cordon.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Lucy took a deep breath as she turned onto the slip road leading to the racecourse. â€No one leaves without my permission,â€ she said to the guard at the gate, noticing the throngs of people standing under the trees.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;This was going to be her most high profile case, as the worst possible time for her. &nbsp;She had to be on her A-game. So did the men plotting just a few miles away.</p><p><br></p><p><b>Chapter 2: The Hunters</b></p><p>&nbsp;Somewhere in Nairobi the small room glowed with the blue neon light from monitors and the claustrophobic reflections it threw in the small shadowy room. The five men inside preferred it this way; always nighttime so there was less chance of discovery. They were fierce in their focus technically savvy, arrogant about their capabilities and exceptionally greedy. This one mission was going to deliver more money than they would see in a lifetime of slogging but the danger, and the stakes were high.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;There was no margin for error inside this pod where technology was the most lethal and the most spectacular. Each had accepted there would be no contact with any one in the outside world for fear of slipping up, sending a signal that could lead to discovery and disaster.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Each had proven their mental strength and almost warped ability to block out the world of lattes, bills, cafes and movies, to stifle emotion and desire, and refusal to trust, except perhaps, each other. They were in it together, embracing a life of falsehoods that hid behind the shattered tapestry of their own lives.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;They tolerated the tight dirty brown cubicles, the cold coffees, overflowing ashtrays, crushed soda cans and stale pizza, the daily dinner, always frozen and stocked up for the week. Tense faces and urgent voices rose suddenly breaking the bleary-eyed methodical typing and mapping.</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œTo the left moreâ€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œI canâ€™t keep up, sheâ€™s moving faster.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œJust step on it will you.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œSheâ€™s changing course, good, slowing down. Here we go.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œThere!â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œPut a lock on it.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;All eyes were glued to the largest monitor in the room. They had their prey in sight and she was beautiful, waiting to be taken.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œThe boss will be pleased.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œItâ€™s taken long enough.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œThe bird had a problem. It took time to fix.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œDonâ€™t let it happen again.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œRight.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œSheâ€™s pretty spectacular.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;â€œGet back to work boys. This is just the beginning of hard days ahead. This is what weâ€™ve been working towards.â€</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;From now on, whatever maneuvers the target made, however unexpected or clever, Master Control was watching for that inevitable moment of weakness, waiting for a mistake and it would happen soon. All that was needed was the agreed upon order from the man calling the shots. He had</p>','/content/images/2015/05/BONIFACE_MWANGI84.JPG',0,0,'published','en_US',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<span style=\"color: rgb(77, 77, 77); font-family: \'Helvetica Neue\', Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; line-height: 18px; background-color: rgb(237, 239, 240);\">Excerpt from my novel, Corvus.</span>',3,'2015-05-09 19:18:21',2,'2015-05-09 19:18:54',2,'2015-05-09 19:18:54',2,0),(13,'b56d3705-87e8-4b4e-818d-8f8bd40234a0','I Battled My Skin and Won','i-battled-my-skin-and-won','<p>I have spent more than a decade of my professional career on international television, my face visible to millions each day. Yet I have spent a lifetime hiding.</p><p>For years, I guard a painful secret: I can\'t bear to look in the mirror. I shrink from bright light. A gaze that lingers a second too long makes me panic. A hot summer day sends me into the shadows.</p><p>I have fish-like scales. There are tiny red islands floating on the surface of my skin. They combine to create continents with jagged surfaces. They turn black and start to smell. There is blood and pus.</p><p>My scalp spits out silver flakes. My ears are filled with crusts. I leave white specks wherever I sit. I float in long, loose clothes. My hands betray me. The sores sit openly. My nails are dented with pockmarks. I find strands of hair on the sheets and pillowcases every morning.</p><p>I suffer from psoriasis. It\'s ravaged my body since I was 8. At its worst my plaques look like leprosy. I feel like a leper.</p><p>\"Please can you leave the pool,\" a woman once told me when I was 22, visiting the Dead Sea in Israel, \"we\'re not comfortable with you in it.\" She is horrified at my body. I am ashamed. I hang my head.</p><p>The landscape from my neck down is chaos.</p><p>So I choose to look away. I am able to dress perfectly in the dark. I can feel my way around a room or a closet full of clothes. I instinctively choose the dimmest corner of a restaurant to sit in. Winters are a relief only because I won\'t stand out covered from top to toe.</p><p>My face is flawless. Not a blemish. Not a mark. Compliments are endless. But I am acutely aware that a horror film unfolds in secret beneath my clothes. I am effervescent and radiant on the outside and rotting inside. Which is the real me?</p><p>The cameras fire up, the red light turns on. I am splendidly made up. I lose myself in the moment. I am energized. I am focused. It\'s only my face. It is floating. It\'s all that exists. It gives me confidence.</p><p>No one has it all. I fight my body and myself all my life. I hit rock bottom many times because of my disease. It seems futile to try anymore. \"Who will ever want me like this\" I cry hysterically at home. \"No one could ever touch me.\" My mother pulls me out self-loathing and defeatism. When I want to give up, she will not let me.</p><p>She becomes an expert on psoriasis. She reads medical journals and approaches alternative healers. She takes me for acupuncture and hypnosis. She mixes various acids in a lab for me to use on my skin and soaks me in a tub full of Dead Sea salt. The rest of the day, I am in a messy, smelly cream. Endless personal research, trial and error bring occasional relief.</p><p>Imagine the nightmarish teen years. I cower from close friendships. No one can know the truth. I never date. Intimacy is out of the question. I have no sensation of touch. The scales are too thick.</p><p>The itch is unbearable. I try and ignore it. It\'s impossible. It agitates me. I use all my strength and I tear at my skin. I am violent. I scratch back and forth until there is blood. It is too raw to do any more. I am filled with rage and humiliated.</p><p>So I disappear in my head, create fictional stories and characters. I play out entire conversations, lives and deaths, stories of courage and cowardice to escape myself. My mind is living a separate life from the body beneath it.</p><p>Somehow, my imagination takes me far. I am in my early 20s, and it\'s the beginning of my career. I am anchoring the prime time shows in Kenya. Tonight is a big opportunity. My game face is on.</p><p>I\'ve spent the afternoon on hair and makeup. As I settle into the anchor\'s chair, I hear the faint rustle of plastic shrink wrap. I have wrapped up my legs and torso in the clingy film after soaking my scales in Vaseline so that the pain is lessened and the putrid smell contained. The director calls out. The floor manager cues me. The lights on, news copy in my hands, I smile and welcome millions of Kenyans into the studio.</p><p>The contrast is sharp -- behind closed doors, I have given up. I am on the floor. I am crying, screaming and itching insanely. My mother cries. I rarely see her cry. The last time was when my grandfather died.</p><p>Then an angel arrives.</p><p>A family friend approaches mum. \"Your daughter looks unwell. She is losing her hair. What is the matter?\" My mother, at her wits end, tells the woman the truth. \"George,\" the angel says. \"Tell her to go to George.\"</p><p>George is a small town in South Africa. I learn there is a clinic that specializes in treating severe skin disease. I adamantly refuse. I have had enough of doctors, hospitals, foul smelling topical creams and hopes dashed. Mum convinces me.</p><p>In a week, I find myself there against my wishes. I withstand the indignity, once again, of being naked, the grotesque lesions under neon light, and I listen to the shocked gasps of the doctors and nurses.</p><p>\"We\'ve never seen it this bad,\" one says in the tiny examination room.</p><p>I glance dully outside the window of my room to see a blue lake and a blue sky amid green trees and grass. Postcard perfect. I count the hours.</p><p>Who could imagine where I am? I am a celebrity in Nairobi, making it big.</p><p>\"What do you do?\" I am asked.</p><p>\"Nothing,\" I respond curtly to any one who dares make conversation with me. I certainly don\'t want to start a conversation about being on television or hosting a radio show for that matter. What would my viewers on KTN and listeners on Capital FM Radio think of me?</p><p>Mind, body and spirit are the focus at this clinic. It sounds insane to me. I am told to do mediation, deep relaxation and creative visualization three times a day. I lie on the floor listening to the voice in charge.</p><p>\"Every day in every way I am getting better and better. I have no desire to eat the foods I know are bad for me...\" I brainwash myself. It works.</p><p>I eat yogurt or bran for breakfast, salads or fish for lunch and chicken for dinner. Nothing tastes good. I yearn for Tabasco. I drink only herbal tea and torrents of water.</p><p>I write a long letter to my psoriasis, describing how it causes me pain, how it hurts my relationships, how it makes me weak. I blame it for not allowing me to be free. I blame it for my rage, my violence, my bullying and my inability to feel loved, for my need for praise and constant reassurance.</p><p>I berate and belittle it. I coax and cajole it. I remind it of my sexless life. I beg and plead for it to go away. Then I thank my psoriasis. It has taught me to have no vanity, more compassion and to withhold judgment.</p><p>I am crying, emotionally drained, and hot underneath my long sleeves and jeans. I take a shovel, pick a spot outside and dig deep. I place the pages into the hole. I plant a tree. I use my hands to touch the earth. Nature seems surprisingly reassuring.</p><p>In this instance, I bury my past. I have said everything I needed to say to my skin. The tree will give life, oxygen. Perhaps it will give me a chance to breathe again.</p><p>A breakthrough.</p><p>It has been two weeks, and I see something no one else can see -- a tiny shift. In the center of one thick plaque, there is a slight thinning. I can discern this little dent only because I have been touching my skin.</p><p>This small success galvanizes me to stick rigidly to the tough diet I have promised to undertake.</p><p>I am ecstatic, fully of new energy. My smile is real. I am positive.</p><p>I return to Nairobi with a new mindset, a sense of control. I maintain the regimen like a military staff sergeant.</p><p>Every 28 days, I see progress. It is small. But it is there. The months pass. The smell stops. The centers of the lesions disappear like small mountains collapsing on themselves. They turn from red to pink to white.</p><p>I watch with fascination the metamorphosis of my skin. The continents on my body move apart with the seismic change in my mind. The scales no longer build. Then they are gone. I can\'t believe it.</p><p>It has been six months. I am clear. I am in remission. I have no scales. I am normal. I am finally free.</p><p>And there is no medication. Only food. \"Let food be thy medicine and medicine be thy food.\"</p><p>When I walk triumphantly into my dermatologist\'s office, she is startled. I healed myself with the power of my mind, I announce. She is shocked. She later tells me she believes there is a place for natural healing in medicine.</p><p>I can\'t say what will work for others, but I believe that diet, mindset and a wonderful support system were the best long-term answers for me. There is a place for light therapy or steroid cream or biological medication, but back then I healed myself from the inside out.</p><p>After my transformation, my family takes me to Mombasa, on the Kenyan coast. I don\'t dread it for the first time in my life.</p><p>I have a new bikini, dark blue with a yellow rim. I have never worn one. It is so soft. It feels feminine. I have never felt like a woman the way I do when I put it on. I see all my curves in a different light.</p><p>The mirror is not my enemy any longer.</p>','<p>I have spent more than a decade of my professional career on international television, my face visible to millions each day. Yet I have spent a lifetime hiding.</p><p>For years, I guard a painful secret: I can\'t bear to look i